[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5
{ Welcome all Chessable members to my first course!  I'm Banh Gia Huy, a young Vietnamese chess lover and Chessable author. My notable achievements include winning the National Youth Championship and being a National Master 'over in Vietnam' as GM Simon Williams said when introducing my course as a finalist of the Create Your Own Course competition. My goal, like many other chess enthusiasts, is to become a Grandmaster. I'm training hard every day to reach that goal, and Chessable is an indispensable part of my daily chess routine.   I've studied so many courses here  (mainly openings courses)  and was  (and still am)  amazed by the fascinating analysis of many Chessable authors, that I dreamed one day I would be among them. I started my analysis from scratch, with virtually no analytical experience and resources. The course was expanded, rechecked, submitted, beta-tested, edited and published. And I am, the moment you are reading this, a Chessable author. It's a dream come true for me, and I'd like to thanks many people for helping me along the way: my coaches for always supporting my work and providing me with useful pieces of advice, my parents for their understanding and patience, the beta-testers of this course @@StartBracket@@ GoldJackal, CautiousChai, Dragonshark and Kapibarr@@EndBracket@@ for their valuable comments to improve the quality of the course.   Lastly, I'm grateful for Chessable's support to get this course edited and published in a tight timeframe. I can mention countless other people who helped me, but let's move on to the Spielmann-Indian.   This course is about the Spielmann-Indian. Don't be ashamed if you don't know what opening that is, I bet many don’t! The Spielmann-Indian starts after the sequence   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  c5  .  With his second move, White excludes many Black openings against  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  like the Nimzo-Indian, Bogo-Indian, Benko/Benoni and the list goes on. This course is intended to be a backup repertoire for supporters of these openings. In the future, I plan to publish a course from Black's point of view against the principled  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  ,  but that's beyond the scope of this course. With  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  ,  White hides his intention for one more move. He may wish to transpose to mainstream 1. d4 openings or follow up with Bf4 reaching the London System.  2...c5  is previously known as an attempt to transpose to Benoni territory, but I'm here to challenge that argument. In this course, I aim to explore the unexplored territories in the infinite possibility world of chess openings. Chess is an enormously complex game that we can never fully understand.  The majority of lines in the course haven't been covered in any source. Originality is the key of this course, is the reason I pick a continuation over another and is a word which you will encounter very often in this course. However, make no mistake that this is a fun but dubious repertoire that can be refuted with correct play. I admit that if White plays in hyper-accurate fashion, in some lines, he might get a slightly favourable position @@StartBracket@@ around 0.5-0.6 according to the engine@@EndBracket@@. However, I have some reasons to allow that.  -There is no direct refutation of Black's fearlessly original play.  -I make sure that in these objectively slightly worse positions, Black's position is easier to play and outline the way for us to continue.  -I give an honest evaluation at the end of every line. If our position isn't better, let it be, and I won't claim otherwise to satisfy my readers. In addition, all lines in this course are checked with the latest version of Stockfish and Leela, so you can be guaranteed the soundness of this course.  With that being said, I believe the appearance of this course will attract several opening analysts and the harsh light of modern engines will eventually cast doubt on several groundbreaking discoveries I made. However, I promise I will provide you with a high level of support and periodically update this course. Most likely, I will even cover alternative options for Black in the critical main lines.  Thanks for your patience to finish reading the introduction to my course! We will move on to the Repertoire Choices file. If you have any questions regarding the course, feel free to ask me in the course forums. }
*

