{ Repertoire Choices file: a brief coverage of the recommended lines } 1. d4
Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5
{ I'm attaching an exclamation mark to this move because it's the only way to challenge the Spielmann-Indian. It's the most critical and ambitious continuation, played in thousands of games.   3.c3  This modest pawn move is met with the unbalancing  3...b6!?  Black has plenty of chances to outplay their opponent in this complex position. Visit this chapter for more details.   3.e3  White protects the d4-pawn in a similar manner as 3. c3, but this time, after cxd4 White can recapture with exd4, thus unbalancing the structure.  3...b6  Again, fianchettoing the queen's bishop is my recommendation. More details can be found here.   3.g3?!  The 'Flashy Fianchetto' was played surprisingly quite often. However, with correct play, Black can control the centre and hold onto it. White must play correctly just in order to reach a balanced position.  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  Is my recommendation. You can find more details in this chapter.   3.dxc5  Our 2nd move is technically a gambit as we leave the c5-pawn hanging, and White greedily captures it. Regaining the pawn is a piece of cake, so the only question is how to do so.  3...e6  Is the most popular move in practice, but in this course, I strive for originality.  My recommendation is   3...Na6!?  This move is, from an objective point of view, at least as good as its alternative. We are proving Tarrasch wrong when putting our knight on the rim of the board. More details can be found in this chapter.   3.c4  As the name of the chapter suggests, this move is really transpositional. This position can arise via several move-orders, for example from the Symmetrical English.  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  Is my recommendation.  5.Nb5  Alternatives to this principled move, 5. Nc2 and 5. Nf3, are covered too.  5...d5  Is the Kasparov Gambit. It would be my proposal if not for the fact that it had been deeply analysed in so many sources, from both sides' point of view.  My suggestion   is  5...Nc6!?  What? We are giving our opponent the opportunity to play  6.Nd6+  and get the valuable bishop pair! However, our tactical resources will come in time, and my analysis proved that  6.Nd6+  isn't the strongest move, but  6.N1c3  .  Visit this chapter for more details. It's the longest chapter in my course, with a lot of sharp and exciting lines. Beware! }
3... b5
{ The Pseudo-Benko! With the text move, Black controls the c4-square and threatens Bb7 in order to win the d5-pawn.   3...e6  Would likely lead to the Modern Benoni or the Blumenfield Gambit. }
4. Bg5 Bb7
{ 4...Qb6  is the most popular move in this position, which got Carlsen's approval. But aren't we the guys to follow the mainstream theory?  My recommendation is   4...Bb7  @@StartBracket@@ even though in the future I will add an alternative option@@EndBracket@@. Allowing White to execute the threat. The resulting positions are enormously complicated, with both sides walking on a thin rope. A mistake can have disastrous consequences, but you will be more prepared than your opponent, provide that you study the 4. Bg5 chapter carefully. }
