[Black "Repertoire Clash"]
[Result "*"]

{ Repertoire Clash: How I dealt against various recommendations from White's point of view. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5
{ 3.c3  Is given in Lakdawala's book 'Play the London System.  3...b6!?  However, he didn't mention this rare and unbalancing continuation, which is analyzed in detail inthis chapter.   3...cxd4  4.cxd4  d5  The only continuation given by Lakdawala, leads to the Exchange Slav. }
3... b5 4. Bg5
{ The principled main line, which was recommended in the book 'e3 Poison' by the famous GM Axel Smith and the Chessable course 'Calm & Collected: 1. d4' by FM Marko Makaj.   4.c3!?  This tricky variation was recommended by the well-known IM Christof Sielecki in the course/book Keep It Simple: 1. d4. Later, it was the choice of GM Milos Pavlovic in his book, 'The Modernized Colle-Zukertort Attack.  4...b4!?  Is my original treatment of this line which was missed by both authors. You can check more details in the4. c3 chapter.   4.e4!?  This venomous gambit is @@StartBracket@@ or will?@@EndBracket@@ be the recommendation of GM Le Quang Liem in his course: Lifetime Repertoires: London System. Even though in practice this option is quite rare, I devote as many as 34 trainable lines for this variation as it's one of the best continuations according to the engine and it has the potential to become one of the future main lines.  4...Nxe4  Is my treatment. You can see my full analysis inthis chapter. }
4... Bb7 5. Bxf6
{ Both authors went for this exchange, which is regarded as the mainline of this course. }
5... gxf6
{ My original recommendation.   5...exf6  Is the only move considered by GM Axel Smith in 'e3 Poison'. }
6. e4 f5
{ In his course, FM Marko didn't consider this option, but instead just mention moves that protect the b5-pawn like   6...b4  and  6...Qb6  This explosive gambit is analyzed in detailhere.   That's the end of the Repertoire Clash. If there is any source that recommends the 1. d4 2. Nf3 scheme of development for White that I didn't mention in this file, please correct me. Thanks! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1.d4  is one of the most principled ways to begin the game, along with  1.e4 }
1... Nf6
{ Here, after   2.c4  Black has numerous options including the Nimzo-Indian, Benoni, Benko Gambit,...  With the tricky text move, White can still transpose into main lines  1.d4  openings while cutting down the amount of theory to learn. Note that White can also play  Bf4  next reaching the London. In this course, I'll show you an aggressive, sound and practical way to challenge this move! }
2. Nf3
{ King's Indian players, like myself, wouldn't hesitate before playing   2...g6  and suddenly we're in a King's Indian while cutting down White's options @@StartBracket@@because he might prefer to delay the knight's development@@EndBracket@@. }
2... c5 { The most ambitious move, hitting White's centre at once. } 3. c3
{ This is a solid move that is played a lot at the club level. White supports the d4 pawn and intends to play Bf4 with a normal London. }
3... b6
{ We go for a queenside fianchetto! This creative approach was advocated by Richard Palliser, who is a brilliant author and analyst. Soon, we will play g6 followed by Bg7 and have a double fianchetto. It's also important to control the e5 square. Black is very solid and can slowly improve his position, while White usually lacks a good plan. Note that in this line positional understanding is far more important than forcing lines.   3...cxd4  will lead us to the boring world of the Exchange Slav. }
4. dxc5
{ One of the most critical tries, but you won't face it a lot as it's not so natural to give up your centre pawn. }
4... bxc5 5. e4
{ The point. White wants to harass the knight with e5. If   5...Nxe4??  then  6.Qd5! }
5... Bb7 { Hitting the e4 pawn. } 6. Bc4
{ A sneaky move, which contains some hidden traps! Whenever you see a pawn hanging, remember to calculate before accepting the gift! }
6... Qc7
{ Declining the offer as   6...Nxe4?  7.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  8.Qb3+  and  6...Bxe4  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Ng5+  Ke8  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Qd5  cannot be any good for Black. }
7. e5 { Otherwise, the e4-pawn will drop. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qxe5+ 9. Be2 Nc6
{ White has insufficient compensation for the pawn, and Black's position is also easy to handle. }
