1. d4
{ 1.d4  is one of the most principled ways to begin the game, along with  1.e4 }
1... Nf6
{ Here, after   2.c4  Black has numerous options including the Nimzo-Indian, Benoni, Benko Gambit,...  With the tricky  2.Nf3  , White can still transpose into main lines  1.d4  openings while cutting down the amount of theory to learn. Note that White can also play  Bf4  next reaching the London. In this course, I'll show you an aggressive, sound and practical way to challenge this move! }
2. Nf3
{ King's Indian players, like myself, wouldn't hesitate before playing   2...g6  and suddenly we're in a King's Indian while cutting down White's options @@StartBracket@@because he might prefer to delay the knight's development@@EndBracket@@. }
2... c5 { The most ambitious move, hitting White's centre at once. } 3. c3
{ This is a solid move that is played a lot at the club level. White supports the d4 pawn and intends to play Bf4 with a normal London. }
3... b6
{ We go for a queenside fianchetto! This creative approach was advocated by Richard Palliser, who is a brilliant author and analyst. Soon, we will play g6 followed by Bg7 and have a double fianchetto. It's also important to control the e5 square. Black is very solid and can slowly improve his position, while White usually lacks a good plan. Note that in this line positional understanding is far more important than forcing lines.   3...cxd4  will lead us to the boring world of the Exchange Slav. }
4. Bf4
{ This 'London Bishop' move is the most popular in the position, even though White has scored poorly in practice. Actually, I found this move one of the easiest to deal with. }
4... Bb7 { We go for the usual fianchetto. } 5. e3 g6 6. Nbd2 Bg7
{ Now, we have both bishops striking down the long diagonals. } 7. h3
{ The usual London prophylaxis, creating a hiding square for the bishop on h2. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ This move doesn't make such a big difference compared to   8.Be2 } 8... d6 9.
O-O Nbd7 { e5 is on the card. } 10. Qe2
{ The main line. It's perfectly natural but allows Black to execute a freeing tactic. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 e5
{ An amazing tactical strike that gives Black the initiative! Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, and White must be careful not to land in a disastrous position. More analysis of this variation can be found here. }
