1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3
{ This is the choice of either the experienced Colle player or guys who are surprised by our second move. }
3... b6
{ Again we opt for the simple but ambitious queenside fianchetto.  Note that   3...cxd4  4.exd4  d5  leads to the Exchange Caro-Kann. If the Caro is in your repertoire, feel free to play it. }
4. c4 { White gains space in the centre. } 4... Bb7 5. Nc3 cxd4
{ Aiming for either an IQP @@StartBracket@@Isolated Queen's Pawn@@EndBracket@@ structure or a position with one more central pawn. }
6. exd4 g6
{ Staying with our double-fianchetto strategy.  I must say that with   6...g6  we sometimes get IQP positions, too, but with a bishop on g7.  That major difference greatly strengthens Black's king safety and adds more firepower to the d4-pawn. }
7. Be2 Bg7 8. O-O { 8.d5  O-O  9.O-O  e6  transposes to the main line. } 8...
O-O 9. Bf4
{ This actually scores well for White in the database, but it's just totally harmless, as Black can hit back in the centre with }
9... d5 10. Ne5 dxc4 11. Bxc4 e6
{ With a complicated position in which Black is not worse. } *

