[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ This advance is clearly inferior as it allows Black to take over the centre easily. Mysteriously, this move was the 5th most popular choice of White, even played more than   3.dxc5  ,  which isn't so ambitious but does give White equality should he wish. Statistically, White's score is a poor 40%, which hinted that we have the opportunity to play for more than equality. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ Actively fighting for the full centre. Understandably, in practice, this is the main move. However, in online chess this is just the third most popular move, with   4...Nc6?!  and  4...g6?!  being the preferred choices. }
5. Nf3
{ This is the second most popular move, and also the first choice of some engines. However, it's a clear concession to retreat the knight like this. }
5... Nc6 { Nothing can stop us from playing d5 next move. } 6. c4
{ Trying to stop or at least slow down d5 } 6... d5
{ We still go for that break! Our triumphs, namely well-placed and more developed pieces will show their value in the open position. }
7. cxd5 Qxd5 { 7...Nxd5  is also perfectly playable } 8. Qxd5 Nxd5 9. Bg2 Ndb4
{ Threatening a game-winning check on c2. White's position is precarious and he can easily fall into a bad position, as illustrated in the corresponding line. }
