[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ This advance is clearly inferior as it allows Black to take over the centre easily. Mysteriously, this move was the 5th most popular choice of White, even played more than   3.dxc5  ,  which isn't so ambitious but does give White equality should he wish. Statistically, White's score is a poor 40%, which hinted that we have the opportunity to play for more than equality. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ Actively fighting for the full centre. Understandably, in practice, this is the main move. However, in online chess this is just the third most popular move, with   4...Nc6?!  and  4...g6?!  being the preferred choices. }
5. Nb3
{ This is the overwhelming main line of the whole 3. g3 variation, played roughly twice the times as   5.Nf3  White's intention is to 'sacrifice' control of the centre, lure Black into pushing centre pawns forward and later attack them from all angles. While that plan can be effective if it's successfully carried out, we can defend our formidable centre quite easily. Afterwards, we will be able to kick White's pieces around and find good squares for our pieces. In short, White's mission is to challenge our centre while we fortify it. There were several high-profile games in this line, most notably Yilmaz, M - Mamedyarov, S, in which the Azeri GM won. }
5... d5 { There is no reason to refrain from occupying the centre. } 6. Bg2
{ At this point, Black has many promising options but as usual, I deviate from the main track as soon as possible. }
6... a5
{ This unexpected @@StartBracket@@in fact it's the 6th popular move, and it scores best among those 6!@@EndBracket@@ and creative thrust is objectively sound and might even bring your opponent out of book by this point. Black's idea is simple: he is threatening a4 to further harass the knight. If White plays a4, he will try to take advantage of the new outpost on b4, as after White ever play c3 his b1-knight will lack a good square. White is forced to choose between two bad options. }
7. a4 { This is the lesser evil. } 7... Bb4+
{ Isn't it just a check and White has plenty of choices to block it? Well, the matter isn't as simple as it seems. We will examine some alternatives for White.  Note that   8.Nc3  d4  wins for Black. }
8. c3
{ Blocking the check with tempo, but as I mentioned before, the c3 square is crucial for White's knight. White will have a hard time with those knights now, and we can afford a tempo for it. }
8... Be7 9. O-O Be6 10. Na3 O-O
{ Black is going to finish development smoothly, with Nc6 and Rc8 to follow. Meanwhile, many of White's pieces are standing awkwardly, and it's just a matter of time before Black exploit that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 3. dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. dxc5
{ In this chapter, we will examine this capture. It isn't so critical, as White concedes the centre to Black, but it has been played by many respectable GMs including Harikrishna, Hammer @@StartBracket@@Magnus Carlsen's second@@EndBracket@@ and Grandelius. Objectively we can claim no advantage, but on the other hand, we have several easy routes to equality. The resulting positions are not dry and symmetrical, so we have excellent chances to fight for the full point.   3...e6  is the most popular move, but precisely for that reason, it's excluded from being our repertoire recommendation, especially if a rarer and equally sound alternative is on the offer. }
3... Na6
{ Tarrasch famously said knights on the rim are dim, but on this occasion he is wrong! Our dynamic and creative knight leap guarantees us easy equality as there is no good way for White to keep his pawn. After recapturing the c5-pawn, we will play b6 combined with g6, reaching the double-fianchetto set-up. }
4. c4
{ Control the d5-square before Black can play d5. Note that this position can also arise via   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.dxc5  Na6  4.Nf3  among others. }
4... Nxc5 5. Nc3 g6 { The standard kingside fianchetto. } 6. g3
{ This is met with the typical } 6... b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O Bg7
{ With an equal game. Next, we will continue with O-O, d6 and Nce4 to simplify the position. }
