[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. c4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4
{ In this chapter, we will look at   3.c4  .  The position after this move can arise via several move orders, most notably  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.Nf3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  White simply gains space in the centre and see what Black do before committing to a plan. Ideally, White wants a Maroczy Bind structure in which he's known to have a stable advantage. This move is, along with   3.d5  ,  White's most ambitious move for an advantage. Against everything else, we can get an equal position with winning chances in a simple fashion, but after 3. c4 we must be well-prepared to avoid a worse position. That's the main reason this chapter has as many as 51 trainable lines. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ At this point Black has many alternatives, for example,   4...Nc6  which leads to the Maroczy Bind structure after  5.Nc3  d6  6.e4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/8/2PN4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  which is recommended in Lifetime Repertoires: Vienna/Benko, a course which I am honour to beta-test. But in this course, I decide to choose a more dynamic course of action. }
4... e5
{ 'What is this anti-positional advance?' You might be screaming inside your head. Black has violated the old positional principle, and proudly gave up the d5 and d6 square. What does he have in return? Black's compensation lies in the potential of his pieces, and the fact that White is slightly behind in development. Actually, the text move is the most popular one for Black in this position, but it won't be so long before we leave the unbeaten but over-analysed paths. }
5. Nb5
{ The critical continuation, immediately takes advantage of the holes left in Black's position. }
5... Nc6
{ This move has been rarely played, compared to the overwhelmingly popular Kasparov Gambit   5...d5!?  In the Kasparov Gambit, Black sacrificed a pawn but retains sufficient compensation due to the activity and development advantage. It would be the perfect candidate for our repertoire, if not for the fact that it was a heavily analysed variation. Several sources have covered this variation from both sides, so let's avoid it. The resulting positions after  5...Nc6  are fresh and unexplored, which is exactly what we want. With this move, we invite White to pick up the bishop pair with  6.Nd6+  ,  which seems like a favourable trade for him. Nevertheless, White must spend some further tempi for that, neglecting his development. }
6. N1c3
{ The most popular move, not rushing to exploit the d6 square, but instead planning to invade on the d5 outpost later. The position very much resembles the Sveshnikov, with the crucial difference is that the pawns are on c4 and e2 instead of c2 and e4. This variation got the approval of many strong players like Eljanov, Neiksans and Esipenko, so this is a major shot by White to crack our Spielman-Indian. }
6... d6
{ As we no longer have Ne4 as a resource against the 6. Nd6+ variation examined earlier, preventing the knight jump is compulsory now. During my analysis, I also noticed   6...Bb4!?  which is quite a fresh direction but after  7.a3!  @@StartBracket@@not  7.Nd6+  Ke7!  @@EndBracket@@ White has the bishop pair while we cannot play the freeing d5 break. }
7. g3
{ This is also possible, with the idea of Bg2, further controlling the d5-square. The only drawback is that White's kingside is slightly weakened, but this isn't so apparent. }
7... a6 8. Na3
{ If Black play passively, White would fully develop his pieces and emerge with a great positional advantage. We need something special here to prove the viability of our brave 5th move.   8...Be7  has been the most popular move, but I feel it's just too meek to cause any trouble. White's score from this point is over 70%, so we won't be recommending it.  What's in Black's favour? He is ahead in development with more active pieces. The a3 knight is misplaced and White will be forced to waste further time with it. How can we exploit the missing of that knight on the kingside? }
8... h5
{ Credit to Leela for finding this amazing resource! This is played once in an amateur game in 2007, which White won. One game cannot show the soundness of a particular opening variation, so I really hope in the future this idea will be repeated! Black is threatening h5-h4 which is not easy at all to deal with. If White ever plays h2-h4 the g4 square would be permanently weakened.   9.Bg5  ,  temporarily holding up the break is the best move, and is covered in-depth here. }
9. h4
{ Now we can develop 'normally' and reach a middlegame which the addition of the h-pawn moves favour us as f5-f4 will come with greater effect. Sometimes the crazy g7-g5 is playable too. }
9... Be6 10. Bg2 Be7 11. O-O Ng4 { White no longer has h3 to kick our knight. }
12. Qd3 g5
{ Open the kingside in spectacular fashion! If you ever get this far in your game, I believe your unprepared opponent will be under a big shock. Even though the cold engine is claiming 0.00 here, in a practical game Black will have better chances because we will be the attacker, while White needs to defend with extreme accuracy. I give some more moves to illustrate the wealth of attacking possibilities available for us in the corresponding line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. d5 b5 4. c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5
{ This is the most critical and ambitious continuation, played in thousands of games. White pushes his pawn forward, thus gaining more space in the centre. In the dream world, White would like to play c4, Nc3, e4 when he has overwhelming control of the centre and can freely choose the optimal placement of his pieces before deciding on a concrete plan. Nevertheless, this move is not without its drawbacks. White needs to focus on the d5-pawn, which is potentially weak. Black also has the important e6 break, that open lines for our pieces and a plan of removing the d5 bridgehead which costs us so much space. }
3... b5
{ Black has several options, for example,   3...d6  or  3...g6  ,  but I like this active move the most. This variation is named the Pseudo-Benko, as the structure is extremely similar to the original Benko Gambit. The only difference is that White has a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on c4, which is clearly in our favour. As White's pawn is not on c4, he is denied the option of taking the gambit. Also, the knight isn't always best placed on f3 because sometimes White wants to have the option of f3 followed by e4 or puts the knight on e2 to support its colleague ọn c3.  To conclude, if the Benko Gambit is dynamic and fighting, then its brother version still contains that flavour while having theoretical soundness and being relatively unexplored. Here White has several alternatives to choose from. }
4. c3
{ This move was first recommended in Sielecki's Keep It Simple 1. d4, a very successful book. When that move was introduced it was played just 9 times, but now, due to the influence of Sielecki's book, this move is being tested more and more at the top level. This is even played by strong GMs such as Gelfand, Demchenko, Bauer, ... The idea of this move is to play   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/2P2N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  5.e4  Nxe4  6.Bxb5  .  It may sound strange, but the exchange somewhat favours White as White will have the e-file and he will no longer face danger from our queenside majority. Later, this move is proposed in Pavlovic's The Modernized Colle-Zuketort. Among all of White's fourth moves, this stands out as the best-scoring one with a whopping 73% @@StartBracket@@ 4. a3? scores 75%, but there are just 2 games in that line so I won't count it @@EndBracket@@. To conclude, this new move is something we should take seriously. The non-forcing nature of it means we have several replies to consider. In this course, I decided to follow an approach that has never been played, natural, and sound. }
4... b4
{ The idea behind this move is pretty simple: White is planning e4 to attack the b5-pawn, so why don't we play prophylactically and prevent that threat in advance? Besides, now it's very hard for White to defend the d5-pawn properly. The c-pawn already moved, so if White play c4 he will lose a crucial tempo. Sometimes White also play e3 with the idea of Bc4. }
5. c4
{ White accepts to waste a tempo. Actually, this is just slightly favourable compared to   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bb7  as we no longer have the bxc4 option available now. On the other hand, now we can immediately strike at White's centre with the familiar }
5... e6
{ Actually in this fresh position White has no less than 7 playable moves to choose from. Here I will cover three of White's possible options. }
6. dxe6
{ This is naturally considered as it's seemingly the only way to maintain the material balance. }
6... fxe6
{ The engines show a slight preference for   6...dxe6  ,  but I generally prefer to recapture toward the centre whenever both options are equally strong. Now we enjoy a space advantage and White must find some way to untangle his pieces. }
7. Nbd2 Nc6 8. g3 Be7 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. b3
{ b2 is literally the only square on the board which welcome the bishop to go to. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ Black has completed his development while White hasn't achieved his desired piece placement, so it's logical to seize the initiative. }
11... d5 { Now, White must do something about that pawn. } 12. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exploiting the hole on c3 is an interesting idea. Of course,   12...exd5  is a valid alternative. I explore this line some moves further here. }
