[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. d5 b5 4. a4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4
{ The third most popular move, with the very concrete idea of undermining the b5-pawn in order to play c4. }
4... b4 { Of course, there is no reason to open the a-file for White. } 5. c4
{ The main move. The idea of this move is to block the queenside completely. Our plan is to fianchetto the bishop on the long diagonal and break out with e6. All of this looks a bit vague at the moment, so let's dive deep into some lines! }
5... e6
{ There are several moves, but I prefer this direct central break as it gives White no chance to support his d5- pawn with e2-e4. A structural imbalance is going to take place, which gives Black excellent winning chances. }
6. dxe6
{ Is rather stale. Now, we have two options: either to complicate life and go for the win or settle with a symmetrical structure with a likely draw. Of course, I prefer the first option. }
6... fxe6
{ Capturing towards the centre and threatening d5 is the way I propose. } 7. g3
{ A kingside fianchetto is a possible option. } 7... Bb7 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O
10. Bf4 { A logical try, threatening Bd6. } 10... Nc6 11. Bd6 Na5
{ For the time being Black proves that the d6-bishop doesn't cause anything while protecting the c4-pawn will cause White a big headache. }
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nbd2 d5
{ Black has the advantage with more space, better minor pieces and White has a lot of weakness in his camp. }
