[Black "3. d5 b5 4. c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c4
{ This move is very interesting. White offers a pawn with the hope that he will regain it later. For example, if we grab the offer with   4...bxc4?!  White will simply continue with  5.Nc3  with e4 and Bxc4 to follow. I would love to recommend  4...b4  as after  5.a4  we would find ourselves transposed to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  and thus cut down the study time. Unfortunately, White has the nasty reply  5.a3!  when I think White's chances are slightly better due to the prospect on the a-file. }
4... Bb7
{ We keep the tension and take aim at the d5-pawn. Actually, now we have transposed into a sideline of the 'real' Benko Gambit   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bb7  .  This is thoroughly covered in Lifetime Repertoires: Benko Gambit. To avoid overlap, I've analysed different replies in the main lines. I will make sure that you will be able to see both my and Swapnil's recommendations. Note that  5.Bg5  transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bb7  5.c4  ,  a line covered later in this course. }
5. Qc2
{ This is the second most popular move behind   5.a4  .  White's idea is that he temporarily ignores the c4-pawn and focuses on shoring up the centre with e2-e4. As we will see later, White sometimes even sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. On our part, we will try to destruct White's centre. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 { This is the only move to defend the d5-pawn. } 6... e6
{ Not giving White a moment to respite. Now White has several choices to defend the d5-pawn, either directly or indirectly. }
7. Bg5
{ The indirect approach with the idea of meeting exd5 with e5 has been tried by several GMs. Again, between some equally good moves, I decided to advocate the sacrificial method which makes White's life the most difficult. }
7... exd5
{ We don't fear losing a minor piece, but we care how much compensation we will get. Understandably this brave move has never been played, but I hope this will change in the future. }
8. e5 Be7 { We want to recapture on f6 with a piece, not a pawn. } 9. exf6 Bxf6
10. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ The smoke has cleared and it's time to evaluate the position. Black has lost a minor piece, but we are currently 3 pawns up with a central majority which restricts White's pieces. The position is balanced with chances for both sides. I investigate this position further here. }
