[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3. d5 b5 4. Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Bg5
{ After examining a bunch of White's fourth moves, finally, we come to the absolute main line, which is played roughly two more times than the second most popular move,   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  .  White's intention is to double Black's pawns with Bxf6. This threat was and is considered so dangerous that Black's most popular moves are  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP2B1/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qb6  and  4...Ne4  ,  refusing to allow White to execute his threat. This move has been played by famous names such as Le Quang Liem, Boris Gelfand, Radjabov, Kramnik versus his rival Topalov, Wesley So and even Garry Kasparov. Additionally, this was recommended in Axel Smith's book e3 Poison. Against this bishop sortie, I propose an uncommon reply which was championed by creative English figures such as Hodgson and Miles. }
4... Bb7
{ We ignore White's threat and counter it with our own attack on the d5 pawn! Obviously,   5.Bxf6  is critical, but we will first look at  5.c4 }
5. Bxf6
{ Damaging Black's pawn structure is the start of the mainline of the whole course. Both recaptures have been tested, but I recommend the one which leads to more dynamic and exciting positions. It wasn't mentioned in Smith's book, so I believe it will catch a lot of your opponents out of book literally! }
5... gxf6
{ There are many advantages of this recapture over   5...exf6    - We will be able to fianchetto the bishop next move   - We capture towards the centre, thus following the principles  - In the future, we can play f5 without worrying about the king's safety   - Our king will be safe in the center most of the time   Of course, this move has its own drawback, namely the weak-looking kingside. The resulting position is extremely complex and sharp as White will try to play against our bishop pair while we strive to open the long diagonals, even at the cost of a pawn or two. You should study carefully in order to understand key strategies/tactics for both sides in this unusual position! At this point  6.e4  is the most popular move which I  analysed extensively, but first, let's look at the restrained  6.e3 }
6. e4
{ White ambitiously seizes space in the centre. This move was played as much as 50 times, but as you can expect from my course, my proposed counter is almost unexplored with just 3 practical examples in the MegaDatabase. As our bishop pair is restricted, we should seek counterplay immediately to avoid being dominated. }
6... f5
{ This move fit the needs of my repertoire: original, sharp and leads to double-edged positions. For a doubled pawn, we managed to  - Soften the defence of the crucial d5 pawn   - Open the long diagonal with tempi   As usual, I want to be honest and don't want to hide any facts. As there is hardly any theory from move 4 onwards, I had to develop them myself. In order to evaluate positions correctly, besides using my own intuition and understanding I often check my recommendations with the engines, as mentioned in the Introduction. Here Stockfish claimed an advantage for White after the greedy   7.exf5  while Leela trusted White to have a slight edge. However, over the time I analysed the engines started to be less optimistic in White's chances, even though Stockfish still believed that White has a small advantage. In my opinion, Black's disadvantage is only numerically around +0.5 and in practice, he has excellent chances.   To conclude, this line is entirely sound in my view. I understand that some readers aren't satisfied yet, but I hope I can change your judgement with the lines presented. Fun fact: This move is played 2 times in my ChessBase Database, both times by the unknown and unrated player Aleksander Emelyanov, so maybe we can call it the Emelyanov Gambit? }
7. e5
{ White insists on his pawn duo, which is doing a good job of restricting our bishops. On the other hand, they are both far advanced and potentially vulnerable. I'm rather surprised that this move has never been tested in OTB chess, even though my online database shows 10 games. }
7... Qa5+ { Protecting the b5-pawn and forcing a concession from White. } 8.
Nc3
{ White invites us to play b4 so he has time to carry out the manoeuver Nc3-e2-f4. However, we have a devious plan to attack the d5-pawn from all angles. }
8... b4 { The first step is to drive the knight away and clear the 5th rank. }
9. Ne2 c4
{ The queen joins the attack in an unexpected way and the central d5-pawn is hit. }
10. Nf4
{ Forced. The knight reached its destined square, but even there it must be harassed. }
10... Bh6 11. Qd4
{ The queen is temporarily holding the position together, and the c4-pawn is hanging. There is no way back for us now, so we should keep the fire burning. }
11... Rg8
{ White's idea is to play   @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/pb1ppp1p/7b/q2PPp2/1ppQ1N2/5N2/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bxf4  12.e6!  with a discovered attack on our rook, so we move our rook away prophylactically à la Kramnik. Both Bxf4 and Rg4 is on the air now. The position is among the most unclear in the whole course, so I advise you to study the following lines with great focus. Both sides have a wide of nonsense-looking tactical resources, but a good thing to know is that with best play from both sides we aren't worse, as Stockfish confirmed after thoroughly investigating the position. }
12. Bxc4 { The critical moment when we must follow a narrow route. } 12... Bxf4
{ The only move to survive. All other moves would give White time to consolidate his impressive centre. }
13. Qxf4 Rg4
{ This skewer wins a bishop, but White will try to get to our king as soon as possible. We will need to show creative defending in this fun position. I devote a large set of trainables to this line. }
