{ This move fit the needs of my repertoire: original, sharp and leads to double-edged positions. For a doubled pawn, we managed to  - Soften the defence of the crucial d5 pawn   - Open the long diagonal with tempi   As usual, I want to be honest and don't want to hide any facts. As there is hardly any theory from move 4 onwards, I had to develop them myself. In order to evaluate positions correctly, besides using my own intuition and understanding I often check my recommendations with the engines, as mentioned in the Introduction. Here Stockfish claimed an advantage for White after the greedy   7.exf5  while Leela trusted White to have a slight edge. However, over the time I analysed the engines started to be less optimistic in White's chances, even though Stockfish still believed that White has a small advantage. In my opinion, Black's disadvantage is only numerically around +0.5 and in practice, he has excellent chances.   To conclude, this line is entirely sound in my view. I understand that some readers aren't satisfied yet, but I hope I can change your judgement with the lines presented. Fun fact: This move is played 2 times in my ChessBase Database, both times by the unknown and unrated player Aleksander Emelyanov, so maybe we can call it the Emelyanov Gambit? }
7. Bxb5
{ After the rollercoaster ride in the   @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb1ppp1p/8/1ppP1p2/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  variation, we now turn our attention to this pawn grab. White let us capture on e4 for now, but in the future, he will regain that pawn quite easily. The Memory Marker for Black in this variation is the queen switch Qd8-b6-g6 in order to protect the kingside. }
7... fxe4
{ After the obvious recapture White can either play   8.Nfd2  or  8.Ng5  ,  but it's likely to transpose. }
8. Nfd2 { The knight on d2 allows White to play Nc3 after Black plays Bg7. }
8... Bg7 9. Nc3
{ With the other knight on g5 it would be a blunder, but here it's fine. } 9...
Qb6
{ 9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Bxd5  would win us a pawn, but  11.Qh5!  seizes the initiative in White's favour. In this course, whenever possible I prefer active piece play over material gain, and this is not an exception. Now, the threat of Bxc3 is real, and the d5-pawn is very weak. In addition, our move also allows a surprising pawn advance. }
10. Ndxe4 { White seems to have everything protected, but we can strike with }
10... f5
{ This bold advance wasn't possible before as White has Qh5+ picking up that pawn, but here we have Qg6 available. White has two possible options: either to go for a complicated endgame or sacrifice a piece for an attack. }
11. Qh5+ { White bails out. } 11... Qg6
{ The queen comes to guard the kingside. } 12. Qxg6+ hxg6 13. Nxc5 Bxc3+ 14.
bxc3 Bxd5
{ After a forced sequence we are at the endgame stage. White is a pawn up, but that is irrelevant as his pawn structure isn't something to be proud of. We have an active bishop on d5 and an already-developed rook on h8 which fully compensate for the slightest material disadvantage. The endgame is equal but by no means drawish, and in a practical game, the player with the better technique is likely to prevail. }
