7. exf5
{ After all these 'sneaky' and 'unimportant' sidelines, we finally come to this natural capture, which can be regarded as the mainline for the whole course. As mentioned, the mainline was tested in several games, specifically 2 times OTB back in 2009. Throughout my short life @@StartBracket@@I was born in 2009!@@EndBracket@@ this move hasn't been tried again, but it was deeply analysed in a lot of sources. You might be asking: which source?   - Firstly, the course which you are going through   - Secondly,... well, wait a minute, I will check   Hope you won't be annoyed with my semi-joke. This course is original, and everything should be original. The self-declared mainline has never received the slightest analysis anywhere, at least to my knowledge. That's the truth. I believe you weren't fooled. Most people would be, but not you. All the Chessable members who give this course a try are original. }
7... Bg7
{ Regaining the f5-pawn isn't such a priority, but to seize the initiative is. White has two ways to defend the b2-pawn:   8.c3  is the strongest and a real attempt at an advantage while  8.Nc3  is meek and easy to deal with. There is also a dubious try, namely }
8. c3
{ Blunting the b7-bishop is actually a serious attempt at a refutation by my naive silicon engine. There is no satisfactory way to deviate since our 4th move 4...Bb7, so this position's evaluation represent the truth of the whole 4. Bg5 Bb7 variation. Initially, I was worried as even at a great depth the engine shows some advantage for White, but eventually, it calms down }
8... Qb6 { Simply protecting the b5-pawn. } 9. a4
{ Undermining the b5-pawn for the c4 outpost, but we aren't going to give him that juicy square }
9... a6 10. Na3
{ More and more forces are directed towards the foot soldier who stepped forward on the 3rd move. It has done its job, and now we should sac it for something else! }
10... Qd6
{ This weird manoeuvre is actually very effective. The d5-pawn is gone, even though at a cost... }
11. axb5 Qxd5 12. Qxd5 Bxd5
{ White shouldn't capture one more pawn because it's poisoned. } 13. Nc2
{ The recommended way for White players. } 13... axb5 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Bxb5
{ Yes, after the opening White is a pawn up. However, our compensation is quite apparent. Firstly, we have the bishop pair which is always an asset in this type of position. Secondly, White's f-pawns are doubled. I suggest you continue with }
15... e6
{ This break is still there, deep in the queenless middlegame! Even though we are undoubling White's pawn, the f-file will be a source of counterplay. For more details of this theoretically critical position, click here }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Systematic 3. c3"]
[Black "3. c3 b6 4. dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1.d4  is one of the most principled ways to begin the game, along with  1.e4  . }
1... Nf6
{ Here, after  2.c4  Black has numerous options including the Nimzo-Indian, Benoni, Benko Gambit,...  With the tricky text move, White can still transpose into main lines 1. d4 openings while cutting down the amount of theory to learn.   Note that White can also play Bf4 next reaching the London. In this course, I'll show you an aggressive, sound and practical way to challenge this move! }
2. Nf3
{ King's Indian players, like myself, wouldn't hesitate before playing  2...g6  and suddenly we're in a King's Indian while cutting down White's options @@StartBracket@@because he might prefer to delay the knight's development@@EndBracket@@. }
2... c5 { The most ambitious move, hitting White's centre at once. } 3. c3
{ This is a solid move that is played a lot at the club level. White supports the d4 pawn and intends to play Bf4 with a normal London. }
3... b6
{ We go for a queenside fianchetto! This creative approach was advocated by Richard Palliser, who is a brilliant author and analyst. Soon, we will play g6 followed by Bg7 and have a double fianchetto. It's also important to control the e5 square.   Black is very solid and can slowly improve his position, while White usually lacks a good plan. Note that in this line positional understanding is far more important than forcing lines.   3...cxd4  will lead us to the boring world of the Exchange Slav. }
4. dxc5
{ One of the most critical tries, but you won't face it a lot as it's not so natural to give up your centre pawn. }
4... bxc5 5. e4
{ The point. White wants to harass the knight with e5. If  5...Nxe4??  then  6.Qd5! }
5... Bb7 { Hitting the e4 pawn. } 6. Bc4
{ A sneaky move, which contains some hidden traps! Whenever you see a pawn hanging, remember to calculate before accepting the gift! }
6... Qc7
{ Declining the offer as  6...Nxe4?  7.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  8.Qb3+  and  6...Bxe4  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Ng5+  Ke8  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Qd5  cannot be any good for Black. }
7. e5 { Otherwise, the e4-pawn will drop. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qxe5+ 9. Be2 Nc6
{ White has insufficient compensation for the pawn, and Black's position is also easy to handle. }
