{ King's Indian players, like myself, wouldn't hesitate before playing  2...g6  and suddenly we're in a King's Indian while cutting down White's options @@StartBracket@@because he might prefer to delay the knight's development@@EndBracket@@. }
2... c5 { The most ambitious move, hitting White's centre at once. } 3. c3
{ This is a solid move that is played a lot at the club level. White supports the d4 pawn and intends to play Bf4 with a normal London. }
3... b6
{ We go for a queenside fianchetto! This creative approach was advocated by Richard Palliser, who is a brilliant author and analyst. Soon, we will play g6 followed by Bg7 and have a double fianchetto. It's also important to control the e5 square.   Black is very solid and can slowly improve his position, while White usually lacks a good plan. Note that in this line positional understanding is far more important than forcing lines.   3...cxd4  will lead us to the boring world of the Exchange Slav. }
4. Bg5
{ The second most played move. White's intention is to take on f6 and cripple Black's structure. In return, Black has the absolutely powerful bishop pair. The resulting position can be quite complex, but objectively Black is fine. }
4... Bb7
{ Not fearing the exchange on f6. As you will see later, we are playing in the same fashion as against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d5  b5  4.Bg5  . }
5. Nbd2 g6
{ Preparing to finish the double-fianchetto set-up. White must damage our structure right now, as otherwise, he cannot explain the bishop's development. }
6. Bxf6 exf6 7. e4
{ The most aggressive move. White wants to take over the centre, which is something we won't let them do. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 d5
{ This is one of the discoveries I made when analyzing this variation. The engine favoured  8...Bg7  instead but after  9.d5  I believe that Black doesn't have enough counterplay with that blunted bishop on b7.   With the text move, we aim for a structure in which the d4-pawn will be a crucial weakness. We are also opening the position which makes our bishops stronger. }
9. Bb5+
{ The immediate check is preferable for White as we no longer have the option of Kf8-g7. }
9... Nd7 10. exd5 Bxd5 11. O-O Be7 12. Re1 O-O
{ Black has finished development smoothly. Next, we will try to put the d4-pawn under pressure with our pieces. }
*

