[White "Another Timid Advance: 3.e3"]
[Black "3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3
{ This is the choice of either the experienced Colle player or guys who are surprised by our second move. }
3... b6
{ Again we opt for the simple but ambitious queenside fianchetto.   Note that  3...cxd4  4.exd4  d5  leads to the Exchange Caro-Kann. If the Caro is in your repertoire, feel free to play it. }
4. Bd3 Bb7 { Controlling the crucial e4-square is the recipe. } 5. O-O g6
{ Again, the standard double-fianchetto. We'll only examine lines in which White delay c4. For coverage of c4 lines, check via  4.c4  move-order. }
6. b3
{ This is an interesting alternative, preparing to challenge us on the long diagonal. }
6... cxd4
{ I wonder why this natural and strong exchange has never been played, as it gives Black a potentially useful c-file. }
7. exd4 Bg7 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. c4 d5
{ Hit back in the centre before White has a chance to play d4-d5. } 10. Re1 O-O
11. Nc3
{ The prophylaxis  11.Bf1!?  is also possible, but after  11...Rc8  Black is fine. }
11... dxc4 { Clarifying the situation in the center. } 12. Bxc4 e6
{ With Na5 to come, Black has a slight advantage. } *

