[White "The Flashy Fianchetto: 3.g3"]
[Black "5. Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ This advance is clearly inferior as it allows Black to take over the centre easily.  Mysteriously, this move was the 5th most popular choice of White, even played more than  3.dxc5  , which isn't so ambitious but does give White equality should he wish.  Statistically, White's score is a poor 40%, which hinted that we have the opportunity to play for more than equality. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ Actively fighting for the full centre. Understandably, in practice, this is the main move. However, in online chess this is just the third most popular move, with  4...Nc6?!  and  4...g6?!  being the preferred choices. }
5. Nb3
{ This is the overwhelming main line of the whole 3. g3 variation, played roughly twice the times as  5.Nf3  White's intention is to 'sacrifice' control of the centre, lure Black into pushing centre pawns forward and later attack them from all angles.  While that plan can be effective if it's successfully carried out, we can defend our formidable centre quite easily. Afterwards, we will be able to kick White's pieces around and find good squares for our pieces.  In short, White's mission is to challenge our centre while we fortify it. There were several high-profile games in this line, most notably Yilmaz, M - Mamedyarov, S, in which the Azeri GM won. }
5... d5 { There is no reason to refrain from occupying the centre. } 6. Bg2
{ At this point, Black has many promising options but as usual, I deviate from the main track as soon as possible. }
6... a5
{ This unexpected @@StartBracket@@in fact it's the 6th popular move, and it scores best among those 6!@@EndBracket@@ and creative thrust is objectively sound and might even bring your opponent out of book by this point.   Black's idea is simple: he is threatening a4 to further harass the knight. If White plays a4, he will try to take advantage of the new outpost on b4, as after White ever play c3 his b1-knight will lack a good square. White is forced to choose between two bad options. }
7. O-O
{ White fails to appreciate the strength of Black's advance, and he will regret not playing  7.a4  after }
7... a4 8. N3d2 Nc6 9. e4 { Break in the center, but } 9... Bg4
{ First exchange the defensive bishop. } 10. Bf3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 d4
{ Then close the centre! It might seem that White's position has been freed a bit but after a closer look, it turns out that Black is a lot better here, as the White knights are stepping over each other.   Nc4 can always be met with b5!. Black also has an important resource, namely }
12. b3 h5 { With a strong kingside attack. If White prevents h4 with } 13. h4
{ He has created further weaknesses, and the simplest way to continue is }
13... Bc5 { With a winning advantage due to White's poor development. } *

