1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. dxc5
{ In this chapter, we will examine this capture. It isn't so critical, as White concedes the centre to Black, but it has been played by many respectable GMs including Harikrishna, Hammer @@StartBracket@@Magnus Carlsen's second@@EndBracket@@ and Grandelius.   Objectively we can claim no advantage, but on the other hand, we have several easy routes to equality. The resulting positions are not dry and symmetrical, so we have excellent chances to fight for the full point.   3...e6  is the most popular move, but precisely for that reason, it's excluded from being our repertoire recommendation, especially if a rarer and equally sound alternative is on the offer. }
3... Na6
{ Tarrasch famously said knights on the rim are dim, but on this occasion he is wrong! Our dynamic and creative knight leap guarantees us easy equality as there is no good way for White to keep his pawn.  After recapturing the c5-pawn, we will play b6 combined with g6, reaching the double-fianchetto set-up. }
4. Nc3 { This inferior move blocks the advance of the c-pawn. } 4... Nxc5 5.
Bg5
{ I don't really understand the idea behind this bishop sortie, which I named the 'Online Bishop' because this is very popular online. Black can gain the upper hand with }
5... Nfe4 6. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ The 'Online Bishop' faces a difficult decision. Objectively  7.Be3  is the best move, but there are some dubious alternatives. }
7. Be3
{ The best, yet unplayed move. Having seen Black's tactical tricks, it is logical to cover the b6-square. }
7... d5 { Securing the dominant position of the e4-knight. } 8. c3 e6 9. g3
{ This fianchetto is White's best try when Black's easiest route to equality is }
9... b6 10. Bg2 Bc5 11. Bxc5 Nxc5
{ Removing the knight from the g2-bishop's line of fire. } 12. O-O Ba6
{ Our bishop has been activated and now it's no less powerful than its counterpart. Black is fine here. }
*

