1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4
{ In this chapter, we will look at  3.c4  .  The position after this move can arise via several move orders, most notably  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.Nf3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  White simply gains space in the centre and see what Black do before committing to a plan. Ideally, White wants a Maroczy Bind structure in which he's known to have a stable advantage. This move is, along with   3.d5  ,  White's most ambitious move for an advantage. Against everything else, we can get an equal position with winning chances in a simple fashion, but after 3. c4 we must be well-prepared to avoid a worse position. That's the main reason this chapter has as many as 51 trainable lines. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ At this point Black has many alternatives, for example,   4...Nc6  which leads to the Maroczy Bind structure after  5.Nc3  d6  6.e4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/8/2PN4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  which is recommended in Lifetime Repertoires: Vienna/Benko, a course which I am honour to beta-test. But in this course, I decide to choose a more dynamic course of action. }
4... e5
{ 'What is this anti-positional advance?' You might be screaming inside your head. Black has violated the old positional principle, and proudly gave up the d5 and d6 square.   What does he have in return? Black's compensation lies in the potential of his pieces, and the fact that White is slightly behind in development.   Actually, the text move is the most popular one for Black in this position, but it won't be so long before we leave the unbeaten but over-analysed paths. }
5. Nf3
{ I've faced this in some blitz games. This line isn't so serious even though it's played occasionally by strong players, but we mustn't give White control of the d5-square too easily. }
5... Nc6 6. Nc3
{ 6.g3  is covered in this variation, via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  5.Nf3  Nc6  6.c4 }
6... Bb4
{ The secret to counter this variation is not to give away the d5-square, even at the cost of the bishop pair! We pin the c3-knight and prepare d5. }
7. Bd2
{ Avoid the ruining of the pawn structure is the way most White players continued in this position. The positional justification is that White wants to force us to exchange on c3 when he will recapture with the bishop.   The e5-pawn would be threatened, the d-pawn would be a constant headache for us and on top of all White has the bishop pair. That seems very desirable for White, but on the other hand, the first player needs some precious tempos for that @@StartBracket@@Bd2, a3 and Bxc3@@EndBracket@@.   Buckle up, you are going to see one of the most thrilling lines I came across when I made this course. It's so exciting, tactical and dangerous that I must bring it to light. }
7... O-O
{ 7...Bxc3  runs into  8.Bxc3  Ne4  9.Qc2!  and White has the advantage.  Apart from the text move, there is another way to buy some chaos:   7...e4!?  8.Ng5  e3!?  While that gambit looks both uncompromising and fresh, there was already some games played and White's king is under no serious threat.  7...O-O  is a modest-looking move, but actually, it's the preparation of a very sharp and aggressive approach, as you will see. }
8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3
{ White has the bishop pair and the structural advantage. Now what? } 9... d5
{ Boom! The board explodes after our crazy, creative, irrefutable and most importantly, original gambit. Black has tried as many as 5 different moves here which sadly doesn't include our gambit.   This is one of the most shocking and pleasing novelty I found when making this course, and I'm proud that I did it just with my brain, not the engine! Don't make a mistake: this gambit is entirely sound even to the materialistic engines. They just prefer calmer alternatives.   However, while these non-forcing options allow Black to protect the e5-pawn and break with d5 later, certainly the immediate break is the best practical bet. For a measly pawn, Black have an open e-file and wild attacking prospect against the bare White king in the centre.   One more thing: this gambit is unnamed. I will name it the Vietnam Gambit, for my lovely motherland. This is quite fair in my opinion: if many countries have their names on chess openings @@StartBracket@@Italian, French, Spanish,...@@EndBracket@@, then why can't my country? If you find this named biased and annoying, then please let me know and suggest your own name. }
10. cxd5
{ Accepting the offer. White is already walking on a thin rope here, and he must play with great accuracy to stay in the game. }
10... Nxd5 11. Bxe5 { This unnatural move should be punished with } 11... Re8
{ Attacking the e5-bishop. } 12. Bc3
{ The only move because from here the bishop is well protected against tricks. Also, with the bishop on g3 White no longer has the Kf2-g3 resource against Nxe3 sacrifices. }
12... Bg4
{ 12...Bf5!?  is also interesting, but I decided to choose the text as the bishop on f5 isn't participating much in the attack. }
13. Nd4 { This loses instantly to } 13... Nf4
{ Attacking e2 and preparing Nd3+. } 14. Nxc6 Nd3+ 15. Kd2 bxc6
{ White is going to lose a lot of material. } *

