12... Bg4
{ 12...Bf5!?  is also interesting, but I decided to choose the text as the bishop on f5 isn't participating much in the attack. }
13. Qd2 { The best defensive try. } 13... Rc8
{ Bring everything to the party! } 14. e3
{ 14.h3?  fails to  14...Bxf3  15.gxf3  Nxc3!  16.Qxd8  Rexd8  17.bxc3  Na5  and Black regains the pawn with a violent initiative. }
14... Bxf3 { Exchanging the f3-knight to free the h4-square for the queen. }
15. gxf3
{ Here, I must say that  15...Nxc3  16.Qxd8  Rexd8  17.bxc3  Na5  is the top engine suggestion, but I don't really like it as White's position is a bit relieved. Therefore, we will opt for the amazing knight sacrifice with }
15... Qh4
{ With engine-like precision, White can hold, but it's an almost impossible task if White isn't prepared. The direct threat is Nxe3. }
16. Qxd5 { What else? } 16... Rxe3+ { Exploiting the pin on the f2-pawn. } 17.
Be2 { 17.Kd1?  Qxf2-+  with Rd8 coming. } 17... Rxe2+
{ Not giving White any moment to respite!  17...Rce8  is met by  18.O-O-O !  and White's king reached safety even though it's still complicated. }
18. Kxe2 Re8+
{ All king moves to the d-file is answered by Rd8, reaching an ending where Black is clearly better due to White's weak king and terrible structure. The only move is }
19. Kf1 Qh3+ 20. Kg1 Re6 { Threatening Rg6+. } 21. Bd2
{ Again, the only move. } 21... Rg6+ 22. Bg5 h6
{ The small pawn is included in the attack, simultaneously attack the bishop and creating a window for the king. }
23. f4 hxg5 24. f5
{ After  24.fxg5??  Black has  24...Nd4!  and wins, so this is required to close the g-file. }
24... Rf6
{ The outcome of the battle isn't clear at all, but Black is doing very well. The h1-rook is out of the game and the king is in trouble. Black's material investment is small: after Rxf5 he will have a pawn and a minor piece to compensate for the exchange. The position is objectively equal, but Black is the side pushing. }
*

