12. Bxe5 Re8 { White faces a choice between bishop retreats. } 13. Bd4 Bf5
{ This is one of the rare cases where I opt for Bf5 instead of Bg4. The difference here compared to other lines is that White has the resource  13...Bg4  14.f3!  Bf5  15.g3  and he will slowly untangle his pieces. If he managed to do so, we would be completely lost as White will have a decisive positional and material advantage. The text doesn't allow f3 with tempo, but most importantly, after a future ...Qh4 the queen will not be obstructed on the 4th rank. }
14. e3 Qh4 { The standard reply against e3. } 15. Be2
{ White is too tired defending, and he accepts a slight disadvantage in order to bring his king to safety. }
15... Rxe3
{ An awesome rook sac!  15...Nxe3  16.Bxe3  Rxe3  17.O-O  is also possible, as Black enjoys a small advantage due to his active pieces. Nevertheless, I don't believe Black has serious winning chances. The text allows White to reach a drawn ending with correct play, but that requires many engine-like moves. We will see how the play might continue. }
16. Bxe3 { 16.O-O?  loses material to  16...Rxe2! } 16... Nxe3 17. g3 Qe4
{ And in practical terms, this is very difficult for White to meet due to Black's numerous threats. There is a computer way out of his troubles, which is not necessary to memorize - I have included it as clickable to show White's best defence.   White's best move here is  18.Bf3!  A stunning counter-attack. With masterly defensive play, White has survived and reached this approximately balanced position. Now, our best is to head for an ending with  18...Nxd1  19.Bxe4  Bxe4  Now, in order to stay in the game, White must find the beautiful  20.f3!  luring the bishop to the f3-square. Play continues  20...Bxf3  21.O-O  Bg4  22.Rfxd1  Bxd1  23.Rxd1  This endgame is most probably drawn with accurate play from White, but could White players possibly find this? It's already the 23rd move and I must say that you needn't remember all this stuff, as they may never appear in your whole chess career.  Instead, I presented those lines as an example of how the play might continue, and give you an idea of plans for both sides. Chess is a really charming game, right?  After a rollercoaster ride, almost all pieces disappeared and we have an equal position. }
