10. Nxe5
{ This is the best move according to the engine, and indeed it's the critical test against the Vietnam Gambit. White doesn't allow Black with the active knight on d5 so we must seek counterplay elsewhere. }
10... Ne4
{ I've analysed the 'natural'  10...Nxe5  too but eventually came to the conclusion that after  11.Bxe5  Qe7  12.Bc3  Rd8  13.c5!  White is better. This positional resource closes the d-file and denies Black any attacking ideas. White has the bishop pair and in the long-term, the d5-pawn will be feeling the heat.   10...Ne4  is much more in the spirit of the Speelman-Indian: we don't fear unbalanced position, we aren't scared by material loss and everything we want is the initiative.   Compared to 10. cxd5, in this variation our compensation is of a positional and long-term nature. There is no direct assault on the White king, but very often we will exploit other factors like White's rotten kingside and structural disadvantage @@StartBracket@@after we take on c3@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Qxd5
{ White tries to refute our gambit by taking all of the offered material. The following sequence is forced. }
11... Nxc3 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. bxc3
{ The game has settled down to the endgame phase. Black has hyper-active cannons @@StartBracket@@rooks@@EndBracket@@, which can penetrate through the unguarded 2nd rank. White is two pawns up, but one of them is doubled, while the other is currently restricting the bishop.   If White ever plays e3 the 2nd rank would be further weakened, so White must lose more time to develop the bishop with g3-Bg2. We will see how the play might continue. }
14... Rb8 15. g3 Ba6 16. Bg2 Bxc4 17. Bxc6 Rb2
{ Black can easily hold this endgame due to our activity. } *

