6. Nd6+ { Very natural, but not best. } 6... Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qa5+
{ A jarring check, based on some tactical points. } 8. Bd2
{ This is the most natural way to block the check. We shouldn't retreat our queen, but counter-attack White's with }
8... Ne4 9. Bxa5
{ White sacrifices a pawn for the bishop pair and vain hopes of trapping the knight. }
9... Nxd6 10. Bc7
{ Only at c7 the bishop can control the retreating squares of the knight. }
10... Nxc4 11. e4 Nxb2 { Bravely gain another pawn. } 12. Nc3
{ ' You've been caught in a trap, ha!' White is thinking. But here, we have a brilliant resource that saves the knight and forces White to find a precise sequence just to reach equality. }
12... d6
{ Taking advantage that the c7-bishop is also short of squares, we gain a tempo for the bishop to come to e6. }
13. Rb1 Kd7
{ The c7-bishop suddenly found itself trapped far from home. A clear two pawns up, Black is close to winning. }
