{ 12.h3  Qxh4  13.hxg4  Qxh1  14.Nd5  Rb8  and while the material is equal, Black's pieces are a lot more active.   With the text move, White intends e3 to defend the weak f2 spot. Even though the engine shows a preference to  12.e3  ,  I believe this move is the most practical and sensible try. }
12... Qxh4 13. e3
{ The only move, as  13.e4  is met with  13...g6!  with Bh6-e3 to follow. }
13... e4
{ 13...Nb4  with the idea of d5 is possible too, but I like this move, as it has a very concrete idea of exploiting the weak d3 and f3 squares in White's camp. Besides, it sets an elegant trap. }
14. Nxe4 Nge5
{ Black is winning, as the dual threats of Qxe4 and Nf3+ cannot be met at the same time. }
15. Bg2 { White seems to defend against both, but } 15... Bh3
{ This deflecting tactic kills all of the first player's hope. After  16.Bxh3  Black wins the queen with  16...Nf3+ }
