{ The most popular move, not rushing to exploit the d6 square, but instead planning to invade on the d5 outpost later. The position very much resembles the Sveshnikov, with the crucial difference is that the pawns are on c4 and e2 instead of c2 and e4.   This variation got the approval of many strong players like Eljanov, Neiksans and Esipenko, so this is a major shot by White to crack our Spielmann-Indian. }
6... d6
{ As we no longer have Ne4 as a resource against the 6. Nd6+ variation examined earlier, preventing the knight jump is compulsory now.  During my analysis, I also noticed  6...Bb4!?  which is quite a fresh direction but after  7.a3!  @@StartBracket@@not  7.Nd6+  Ke7!  @@EndBracket@@ White has the bishop pair while we cannot play the freeing d5 break. }
7. Nd5
{ This is the second most popular move, but in my opinion, a harmless try compared to  7.Bg5  . }
7... Nxd5
{ We ensure that White can never land a piece into the d5 outpost in the future, as he is literally forced to recapture with the pawn. }
8. cxd5 { Now we have to make a decision with the knight. } 8... a6
{ 8...Nb8  is perfectly playable too, but I prefer the relocating of the knight to g6 from e7. The knight can support a potential ...f5 break from that square.  8...Ne7?  would be a big blunder due to  9.Qa4!  ,  a typical idea known from the 'original' Sveshnikov.   White threatens a deadly discovered check which we cannot stop. Hence, this in-between move is needed to kick the knight back first. In the Sveshnikov, the e2-pawn would be on c4 here so we can't insert this little advance. One of the several pluses of this variation over the Sveshnikov, right? }
9. Nc3 Ne7
{ The engine dislikes this move, as it shows an evaluation of around 0.8, but I believe it's both sound and offers good practical chances. }
10. e4 Ng6
{ From here the knight can jump into f4, causing White a headache. The Bf8-e7-g5 manoeuver to swap the 'bad' bishop is possible too. }
11. Bd3 { The only move played so far. Actually, it was played back in 2010! }
11... Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Ne2 Bg5
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishop is usually in our favour, and this is no exception. }
14. Qb3 b5
{ Both sides have their chances in this balanced middlegame. Black should develop his bishop with Bd7, and fight for control of the c-file. }
*

