{ In this chapter, we will look at  3.c4  .  The position after this move can arise via several move orders, most notably  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.Nf3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  White simply gains space in the centre and see what Black do before committing to a plan. Ideally, White wants a Maroczy Bind structure in which he's known to have a stable advantage. This move is, along with   3.d5  ,  White's most ambitious move for an advantage. Against everything else, we can get an equal position with winning chances in a simple fashion, but after 3. c4 we must be well-prepared to avoid a worse position. That's the main reason this chapter has as many as 51 trainable lines. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ At this point Black has many alternatives, for example,   4...Nc6  which leads to the Maroczy Bind structure after  5.Nc3  d6  6.e4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/8/2PN4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  which is recommended in Lifetime Repertoires: Vienna/Benko, a course which I am honour to beta-test. But in this course, I decide to choose a more dynamic course of action. }
4... e5
{ 'What is this anti-positional advance?' You might be screaming inside your head. Black has violated the old positional principle, and proudly gave up the d5 and d6 square.   What does he have in return? Black's compensation lies in the potential of his pieces, and the fact that White is slightly behind in development.   Actually, the text move is the most popular one for Black in this position, but it won't be so long before we leave the unbeaten but over-analysed paths. }
5. Nb5
{ The critical continuation, immediately takes advantage of the holes left in Black's position. }
5... Nc6
{ This move has been rarely played, compared to the overwhelmingly popular Kasparov Gambit.  5...d5!?  In the Kasparov Gambit, Black sacrificed a pawn but retains sufficient compensation due to the activity and development advantage.   It would be the perfect candidate for our repertoire, if not for the fact that it was a heavily analyzed variation. Several sources have covered this variation from both sides, so let's avoid it.   The resulting positions after  5...Nc6  are fresh and unexplored, which is exactly what we want. With this move, we invite White to pick up the bishop pair with  6.Nd6+  ,  which seems like a favourable trade for him. Nevertheless, White must spend some further tempi for that, neglecting his development. }
6. N1c3
{ The most popular move, not rushing to exploit the d6 square, but instead planning to invade on the d5 outpost later. The position very much resembles the Sveshnikov, with the crucial difference is that the pawns are on c4 and e2 instead of c2 and e4.   This variation got the approval of many strong players like Eljanov, Neiksans and Esipenko, so this is a major shot by White to crack our Spielmann-Indian. }
6... d6
{ As we no longer have Ne4 as a resource against the 6. Nd6+ variation examined earlier, preventing the knight jump is compulsory now.  During my analysis, I also noticed  6...Bb4!?  which is quite a fresh direction but after  7.a3!  @@StartBracket@@not  7.Nd6+  Ke7!  @@EndBracket@@ White has the bishop pair while we cannot play the freeing d5 break. }
7. Bg5
{ In the spirit of the Sveshnikov, White pins the f6 knight, the chief defender of the d5 square. }
7... a6 { Now White has two options. } 8. Bxf6
{ Destroying our pawn structure at the cost of the bishop pair. } 8... gxf6
{ Of course  8...Qxf6  loses to  9.Nd5 } 9. Na3 f5
{ We actively use our doubled pawns as an asset and gain space in the centre. }
10. g3
{ The bishop is, as usual, best placed on g2, but this runs into the standard }
10... h5 { We are planning h5-h4, get rid of our isolated h-pawn. } 11. h4 Be6
12. Bg2 { This is met by the same recipe. } 12... e4
{ Black has great play with the bishop pair pointing at the weaknesses in White's position. A sample line is }
13. O-O Bg7 14. Qd2 Be5 15. Nd5 Ne7
{ Neutralizing the d5-knight. Black is fine in this hyper-complex middlegame. }
