[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. d5 b5: 4th move Meek Alternatives"]
[Black "4. Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5
{ This is the most critical and ambitious continuation, played in thousands of games. White pushes his pawn forward, thus gaining more space in the centre. In the dream world, White would like to play c4, Nc3, e4, with overwhelming control of the center. White can freely choose the optimal placement of the pieces before deciding on a concrete plan. Nevertheless, this move is not without drawbacks. White needs to focus on the d5-pawn, which is potentially weak. Black also has the important e6 break, opening lines for his pieces and removing the d5 bridgehead which costs us so much space. }
3... b5
{ Black has several options, for example,  3...d6  or  3...g6  ,  but I like this active move the most. This variation is named the Pseudo-Benko, as the structure is extremely similar to the original Benko Gambit. The only difference is that White has a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on c4, which is clearly in our favour. As White's pawn is not on c4, he is denied the option of taking the gambit. Also, the knight isn't always best placed on f3 because sometimes White want to have the option of f3 followed by e4 or put the knight on e2 to support its colleague ọn c3.   To conclude, if the Benko Gambit is dynamic and fighting, then its brother version still contains that flavour while having theoretical soundness and being relatively unexplored. Here White has several alternatives to choose from. }
4. Bf4
{ Some enthusiastic London player will play Bf4 regardless of what Black does. This move is rather pointless as the bishop doesn't really belong on f4 and the d5-pawn is in real trouble after }
4... Bb7 5. d6
{ Forced, as otherwise the d5-pawn drops with a big advantage for Black. } 5...
Nc6
{ The cool idea of maintaining the tension is known from the   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  variation. }
6. Nc3 { The best move, developing the knight and attack the b5-pawn. } 6... a6
7. dxe7 Bxe7 8. e4
{ 8.e3?  d5!  and again Black has the centre. The text move is practically forced, fighting for control of the d5-square. }
8... d6 { Preventing e5. } 9. Be2
{ This doesn't allow the d5 break, but does nothing to defend the crucial e4-pawn. }
9... O-O 10. O-O Re8 { We start lining up on the e4-pawn. } 11. Re1 h6
{ Preventing Bg5 and prepare Bf8. } 12. Bd3 Bf8
{ The e4-pawn is under fire. Next, we can play Nb4 to pick up the bishop pair or a timely c4 to weaken the defence of the e4-pawn. }
*

