1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c3
{ This move was first recommended in Sielecki's Keep It Simple 1. d4, a very successful book. When that move was introduced it was played just 9 times, but now, due to the influence of Sielecki's book, this move is being tested more and more at the top level. This is even played by strong GMs such as Gelfand, Demchenko, Bauer, ... The idea of this move is to play   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/2P2N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  5.e4  Nxe4  6.Bxb5  .  It may sound strange, but the exchange somewhat favours White as White will have the e-file and he will no longer face danger from our queenside majority. Later, this move is proposed in Pavlovic's The Modernized Colle-Zuketort. Among all of White's fourth moves, this stands out as the best-scoring one with a whopping 73% @@StartBracket@@ 4. a3? scores 75%, but there are just 2 games in that line so I won't count it @@EndBracket@@. To conclude, this new move is something we should take seriously. The non-forcing nature of it means we have several replies to consider. In this course, I decided to follow an approach that has never been played, natural, and sound. }
4... b4
{ The idea behind this move is pretty simple: White is planning e4 to attack the b5-pawn, so why don't we play prophylactically and prevent that threat in advance? Besides, now it's very hard for White to defend the d5-pawn properly. The c-pawn already moved, so if White play c4 he will lose a crucial tempo. Sometimes White also play e3 with the idea of Bc4. }
5. c4
{ White accepts to waste a tempo. Actually, this is just slightly favourable compare to   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bb7  as we no longer have the bxc4 option available now. On the other hand, now we can immediately strike at White's centre with the familiar }
5... e6
{ Actually in this fresh position White has no less than 7 playable moves to choose from. Here I will cover three of White's possible options. }
6. Qc2
{ The idea behind this crafty queen move is that   6...exd5  7.cxd5  Nxd5?  8.Qe4+  picks up a piece. Also, White is intending e2-e4 to fortify his centre. Black can counter with an equally creative queen move,  6...exd5  7.cxd5  Qe7!?  and now we are threatening Nxd5 while preventing e2-e4. The problem is that the whole plan looks unnatural and even after losing the d5-pawn White will have great compensation, mostly based on the unfortunate placement of the Black queen. I also had in mind the idea of blocking the kingside with d6 followed by e5, but here White can take advantage of not closing the queenside yet like in the  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bb7  5.a4  variation and open the queenside with a quick a3. The solution is to keep the tension so we reserve the option of exd5 at the appropriate moment. }
6... g6 { The bishop is best placed on the long diagonal. } 7. e4 d6
{ Of course, we never allow White to play e5. } 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. a3
{ Now we are ready to meet this break with } 10... a5
{ Keeping the pawn structure intact. } 11. Be3
{ 11.axb4?!  cxb4  leads nowhere for White, as Black now has a wonderful outpost on c5. }
11... Na6
{ Black has managed to defend against White's threats, and now it's time to switch attention to the other wing. Black will play e5 next, with typical King's Indian play. }
