[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Undermine the Underminer: 4. a4"]
[Black "4. a4 b4 5. e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4
{ The third most popular move, with the very concrete idea of undermining the b5-pawn in order to play c4. }
4... b4 5. e3 { Preparing Bc4 to defend the d5-pawn. } 5... Bb7 6. Bc4 e6
{ Pressuring d5 is the key theme in this variation. Here the situation is unfavourable for White as he cannot support the pawn further and is therefore forced to take the e6-pawn. }
7. dxe6 fxe6
{ Of course, we recapture with the f-pawn to open the f-file and gain a central pawn majority. }
8. O-O Be7 9. b3 { b2 is the only square for the passive dark-squared bishop. }
9... d5 10. Bd3 Bd6 { Preventing a potential Ne5 followed by f4. } 11. Bb2 O-O
12. Nbd2 Nbd7 13. Qe2 { White intends to push e4, so Black prevents it. } 13...
Ne4
{ Black has a clear advantage due to the space advantage and energetic pieces. We will start a killer attack on the kingside, with all the pieces pointing there. }
