[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Undermine the Underminer: 4. a4"]
[Black "5. Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4
{ The third most popular move, with the very concrete idea of undermining the b5-pawn in order to play c4. }
4... b4 5. Bg5
{ This line bears some similarities with the 'main line of the main lines' after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  .  White is trying to get an improved version of that line, having gained the c4-square for his knight.   Nevertheless, our b4-pawn is doing a great job of restricting White's knight from coming to c3, and both the a4 and d5 pawns are vulnerable. Our treatment is the same as after 4. Bg5. }
5... Bb7 6. Bxf6
{ Crippling our pawn structure, but as you will see, Black can use the doubled pawns to our advantage and make White regrets exchanging the important bishop! }
6... gxf6 7. e4 { This was played by GM Jorge Cori. } 7... f5
{ Woohoo! The idea of this mind-blowing sacrifice is borrowed from the 4. Bg5 chapter. It's the same position with the only difference being the insertion of a4 and b4. This declines White the option to play Bxb5.   Secondly and no less importantly, White cannot play Nc3, which is the normal development of the knight. And did I forgot to mention that this is a novelty which I discovered when making this course? }
8. e5
{ This move has the idea of maintaining the pawn due of d5 and e5 in order to restrict Black's bishops on the long diagonals. However, a significant drawback of this move is that both of the pawns are weak, especially d5. We should start our counterplay with }
8... Bg7 9. Bc4 e6 { First step in targeting d5. } 10. O-O Na6
{ Preparing Nc7 is the second step. } 11. Re1 Nc7
{ Finally, White is forced to either push the pawn forward or exchange on e6, fixing the pawn structure and open the long diagonal for our light-squared bishop. }
12. d6
{ 12.dxe6  dxe6  is fine for Black. The position is objectively balanced, but I'd definitely take Black here as the bishop pair is really threatening. If given the move, Black would exchange on d1 and f3 followed by capturing on e5 with a winning position due to material advantage and White's poor structure. }
12... Nd5
{ The e5-pawn is weak, and if it ever falls, the d6-pawn will fall too. Black has a powerful knight on d5 and a monster bishop sitting on b7. Next, Black will put pressure on White's centre with a combination of Nf4-g6, O-O and the key part - f6! }
