1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4
{ The third most popular move, with the very concrete idea of undermining the b5-pawn in order to play c4. }
4... b4 5. Bg5
{ This line bears some similarities with the 'main line of the main lines' after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  .  White is trying to get an improved version of that line, having gained the c4-square for his knight.   Nevertheless, our b4-pawn is doing a great job of restricting White's knight from coming to c3, and both the a4 and d5 pawns are vulnerable. Our treatment is the same as after 4. Bg5. }
5... Bb7 6. Bxf6
{ Crippling our pawn structure, but as you will see, Black can use the doubled pawns to his advantage and make White regret exchanging the important bishop! }
6... gxf6 7. e4 { This was played by GM Jorge Cori. } 7... f5
{ Woohoo! The idea of this mind-blowing sacrifice is borrowed from the 4. Bg5 chapter. It's the same position with the only difference being the insertion of a4 and b4. This declines White the option to play Bxb5.   Secondly and no less importantly, White cannot play Nc3, which is the normal development of the knight. And did I forgot to mention that this is a novelty which I discovered when making this course? }
8. exf5 { The acceptance of any gambit should be critical. } 8... Bg7 9. c3
{ 9.Qc1  drops a pawn to  9...Bxd5 } 9... Na6
{ Initially, I recommended  9...O-O  ,  but as I went deeper I saw that  10.Bc4  e6  11.O-O!  is very pleasant for White. The text move is played with the idea of Nc7 and e6 to attack d5 from a different angle. }
10. Bc4 { Prophylactically defending the d5-pawn. } 10... Nc7 11. O-O O-O
{ Black is absolutely fine here. I will show a sample line in order to illustrate how play might proceed from this point. }
12. Qd3 e6
{ As a rule of thumb, whenever we have managed to carry out this break unharmed, we are out of danger. }
13. fxe6 { 13.d6  Nd5  14.fxe6  fxe6  transposes to the main line. } 13... fxe6
14. d6
{ 14.dxe6?  d5!  allows Black to seize the initiative and push White's pieces back. The e6-pawn is a little matter, as we can easily pick it up later. }
14... Nd5
{ Black's initiative is surprisingly dangerous, and White must be extremely careful not to fall in an immediately lost position.   The only move to save him is  15.Bxd5  ,  voluntarily giving up the bishop pair as otherwise, Black can organize an unstoppable attack with Nf4, Qf6-g6 and even Nxg2 in some lines. For example, after  15.Nbd2?  Nf4  16.Qc2?!  Nxg2!  17.Kxg2  Black has  17...Qg5+  utilizing the fact that the f3-knight is pinned.  18.Kh1  Rxf3!  is a brilliant game-ender. }
