[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Undermine the Underminer: 4. a4"]
[Black " 5. c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4
{ The third most popular move, with the very concrete idea of undermining the b5-pawn in order to play c4. }
4... b4 5. c4
{ The main move. The idea of this move is to block the queenside completely.  5...bxc3  isn't really an option due to  6.Nxc3  with smooth development and switch the focus to the kingside where White has more space.    Our plan is to fianchetto the bishop on the long diagonal and break out with e6. All of this looks a bit vague at the moment, so let's dive deep into some lines! }
5... e6
{ There are several moves, but I prefer this direct central break as it gives White no chance to support his d5 pawn with e2-e4. A structural imbalance is going to take place, which gives Black excellent winning chances. }
6. Bg5 { The main move, pinning the f6-knight. } 6... h6
{ This is our treatment! We force White to make an unpleasant decision: either to give up the bishop pair or retreat, allowing us to break the pin with g5. }
7. Bxf6
{ White's idea is to lure our queen out in the open and gain some useful tempi kicking it while improving his centre. }
7... Qxf6 { The b2-pawn is hanging, so White must decide what to do with it. }
8. Qc2 { The only move ever played in this position. } 8... g5
{ 8...g6  is also possible, but this time we should push the pawn all the way to g5 as our queen might go to g6 in the future. Also, sometimes g5-g4 can be an irritating threat. }
9. Nbd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O
{ Seemingly this is the best way of defending the b2-pawn, castling into the queenside where the structure is 'blocked' so that the king will be safe. Our reply is a rude awakening! }
10... b3
{ A brilliant typical pawn sacrifice. For a minimal amount of material, we secure a dream outpost on b4 for the knight, an open b-file for the rook. White's king will come under fire pretty soon. }
11. Qxb3 O-O
{ Our compensation is long-term so we don't need to rush, just simple development suffices. }
12. e4 { White threatens e5 to block the diagonal, so we play } 12... d6 13. e5
{ This move shows how desperately is White to block the diagonal. Otherwise, we will simply play Na6 and Rb8 with a killing attack. }
13... dxe5 14. Ne4 Qg6
{ And here is the point of our 8th move, to secure g6 for our queen! From this square the queen eyes the b1-h7 diagonal and participate in the attack. Black is clearly winning. }
