5. Nbd2
{ The third most popular move, and a decent one. White's idea is similar to  5.Qc2  : he wants to play e2-e4 and ignores the c4-pawn for the time being. We treat it with the same method as after 5. Qc2. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 e6
{ We are at a tabiya of the 5. Nbd2 variation. At this point  7.dxe6  is the mainline, but  7.Bxc4  is a respectable alternative. }
7. Bxc4
{ This move contains some nasty traps. With best play, we can win a pawn without getting into trouble, but cannot claim any advantage either.   This natural move contains some nasty trap. With best play we can win a pawn without getting into trouble, but cannot claim any advantage either }
7... exd5 8. exd5 Qe7+
{ This intermediate check is the key. We highlight White's awkward coordination and practically force his king to move. }
9. Kf1
{ The king has been denied of castling right, so we can safely take the pawn. }
9... Bxd5 10. Bxd5 Nxd5
{ We are slightly behind in development, but White's king is also not conveniently placed. In the next few moves, we should hurry to develop our kingside before the h1-rook joins the battle. }
11. g3 { White intends Kg2 and Re1 winning the queen. } 11... Nc7
{ The key manoeuver, bringing the knight to the e6 square where it will act as a barricade on the e-file. }
12. Kg2 Qd6
{ Another important resource, discouraging Nc4 and preparing Be7 at the same time. }
13. Qb3 Ne6
{ We have nearly consolidated and it's White who is fighting for equality. Next, we will play @@StartBracket@@ in an order depends on White's play@@EndBracket@@ Be7, Qc6/Qc7 and castle, most likely returning the pawn in the process. }
