[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poisonous Gift: 4. c4"]
[Black "5. Nbd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c4
{ This move is very interesting. White offers a pawn with the hope that he will regain it later. For example, if we grab the offer with  4...bxc4?!  White will simply continue with  5.Nc3  with e4 and Bxc4 to follow.   I would love to recommend  4...b4  as after  5.a4  we would find ourselves transposed to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  and thus cut down the study time. Unfortunately, White has the nasty reply  5.a3!  when I think White's chances are slightly better due to the prospect on the a-file. }
4... Bb7
{ We keep the tension and take aim at the d5-pawn. Actually, now we have transposed into a sideline of the 'real' Benko Gambit:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bb7  .  This is thoroughly covered in Lifetime Repertoires: Benko Gambit. To avoid overlap, I've analysed different replies in the main lines. I will make sure that you will be able to see both my and Swapnil's recommendations.   Note that  5.Bg5  transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bb7  5.c4  ,  a line covered later in this course. }
5. Nbd2
{ The third most popular move, and a decent one. White's idea is similar to  5.Qc2  : he wants to play e2-e4 and ignores the c4-pawn for the time being. We treat it with the same method as after 5. Qc2. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 e6
{ We are at a tabiya of the 5. Nbd2 variation. At this point  7.dxe6  is the mainline, but  7.Bxc4  is a respectable alternative. }
7. dxe6
{ White presents us with a decision: which pawn should we recapture with?  Normally in this course, I prefer Freddie the f-pawn, but in this case, White has the annoying  7...fxe6  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxc4  with a sizeable advantage due to our weakened kingside and the strong knight on c4.   For that reason, this time we should recapture with the other pawn. }
7... dxe6 8. e5
{ Creating a bridgehead on e5 and driving our defensive knight away.   8...Nd5  is the most popular and arguably natural move, but I believe you understand what I meant: a rare and original alternative is preferred. }
8... Ne4
{ Strictly speaking this is not original as this was innocently played in a game between two amateurs. The idea is simple: We have less space, so it's in our favour to swap some pieces. }
9. Bxc4 Nxd2 10. Bxd2 Nc6
{ Black's position is so harmonious that I think we can stop at this point. For the time being White has no prospect of a kingside attack, and on the next move, we will play Be7 to rule out any Ng5 ideas.   Our queenside structure is broken, but in return, we own the semi-open b-file and the possibility of Nb4-d5 or even Nd4. The position is dynamically balanced, and in practice, the better and more experienced player is likely to prevail. }
