5... bxc4 6. e4 { This is the only move to defend the d5-pawn. } 6... e6
{ Not giving White a moment to respite. Now White has several choices to defend the d5-pawn, either directly or indirectly. }
7. Bg5
{ The indirect approach with the idea of meeting exd5 with e5 has been tried by several GMs. Again, between some equally good moves, I decided to advocate the sacrificial method which makes White's life the most difficult. }
7... exd5
{ We don't fear losing a minor piece, but we care how much compensation we will get. Understandably this brave move has never been played, but I hope this will change in the future. }
8. e5 Be7 { We want to recapture on f6 with a piece, not a pawn. } 9. exf6 Bxf6
10. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ The smoke has cleared and it's time to evaluate the position. Black has lost a minor piece, but we are currently 3 pawns up with a central majority which restricts White's pieces.   The position is balanced with chances for both sides. I will show some sample lines so you will develop a feeling of the position and be familiar with the tricks. }
11. Qe2+
{ White is trying to exchange queens after which his defence will be a lot easier. Of course, we are not going to fall into his plan. }
11... Kd8
{ Even at the cost of neglecting the long-term safety of the king, we must continue to harass White's pieces! Re8 is the threat, so White is forced to move his queen again. }
12. Qd2 Re8+ 13. Be2 d4 { And now the pawns is ready for action! } 14. O-O d5
{ Black's doubled pawns is marching down the board. White's task of defending is far from easy as our compensation is always there with more active pieces, that impressive pawn wall in the centre and the open e-file.   White will need to give back material at some point to free his pieces. Next, we will continue with Nc6, Kc7, Rhd8,... with amazing long-term compensation for the piece. }
