{ This is the second most popular move behind  5.a4  .  White's idea is that he temporarily ignores the c4-pawn and focuses on shoring up the centre with e2-e4.   As we will see later, White sometimes even sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. On our part, we will try to destruct White's centre. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 { This is the only move to defend the d5-pawn. } 6... e6
{ Not giving White a moment to respite. Now White has several choices to defend the d5-pawn, either directly or indirectly. }
7. dxe6
{ White decides that he cannot sustain the pressure on d5 and force matters. Here Swapnil recommended 7...dxe6, which will inevitably equalize for Black, but I prefer to complicate matters and get a typical Benko structure. }
7... fxe6 { Following the old principles, we capture towards the centre. } 8.
e5 { This gives Black the d5 square for free and makes itself a target. } 8...
Nd5 9. Bxc4 Nc6 10. O-O Qc7
{ It will be very hard for White to defend the pawn in the long-term without any concessions. }
11. Re1 Nd4
{ We can also proceed in the slow mode with  11...Be7  , but I like this one as it creates new problems for White to solve. }
12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Nd2 Rc8
{ The e5-pawn is weak while the c4-bishop is pinned. White's knight is blocking the development of the dark-square bishop. Black will continue development with Be7, O-O and launch an attack against White's various weak points, for example, Nf4 eyeing g2 is an idea. }
