7... fxe6 { Following the old principles, we capture towards the centre. } 8.
Nc3
{ This is played even less than  8.e5  but is the better way to go for White as he defends the pawn without creating any more weakness.   A fun fact is that Bluebaum @@StartBracket@@now a strong GM@@EndBracket@@ handled the Black side once in this position when his rating was only 1900. Despite that fact, the future GM found the correct move. }
8... Nc6 { Eyeing the sensitive d4 square. } 9. Bxc4 Nd4
{ Once more this knight leap is favourable to us as after  10.Nxd4?  cxd4  Black wins a free pawn on e4. }
10. Qd3 { This move serves both purposes of defending f3 and e4. } 10... Rc8
{ We are setting White a sneaky and hard-to-spot trap. It's up to our opponent whether he generously accepts the poisoned gift. }
11. Nxd4
{ It might sound harsh, but White is already lost! Let's see how can we prove it. }
11... cxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc5 { The queen is chased. } 13. Qd3 Ng4
{ And so the f2-pawn. The threat of Nxf2 is incredibly hard to stop. For example  14.Nd1  loses material to  14...Bb4+!  15.Nc3  Ne5-+  and the c4-bishop is lost. }
14. O-O { Castling is no better either. } 14... Qc7
{ Black threatens mate and indirectly takes aim at the c4-bishop at the same time. }
15. g3 Nxf2
{ Black is simply winning as after  16.Rxf2  Bxf2  followed by Qxc4 we will emerge an exchange up with an unstoppable attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poisonous Gift: 4. c4"]
[Black "5. Qc2 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c4
{ This move is very interesting. White offers a pawn with the hope that he will regain it later. For example, if we grab the offer with  4...bxc4?!  White will simply continue with  5.Nc3  with e4 and Bxc4 to follow.   I would love to recommend  4...b4  as after  5.a4  we would find ourselves transposed to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  and thus cut down the study time. Unfortunately, White has the nasty reply  5.a3!  when I think White's chances are slightly better due to the prospect on the a-file. }
4... Bb7
{ We keep the tension and take aim at the d5-pawn. Actually, now we have transposed into a sideline of the 'real' Benko Gambit:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bb7  .  This is thoroughly covered in Lifetime Repertoires: Benko Gambit. To avoid overlap, I've analysed different replies in the main lines. I will make sure that you will be able to see both my and Swapnil's recommendations.   Note that  5.Bg5  transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bb7  5.c4  ,  a line covered later in this course. }
5. Qc2
{ This is the second most popular move behind  5.a4  .  White's idea is that he temporarily ignores the c4-pawn and focuses on shoring up the centre with e2-e4.   As we will see later, White sometimes even sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. On our part, we will try to destruct White's centre. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 { This is the only move to defend the d5-pawn. } 6... e6
{ Not giving White a moment to respite. Now White has several choices to defend the d5-pawn, either directly or indirectly. }
7. dxe6
{ White decides that he cannot sustain the pressure on d5 and force matters. Here Swapnil recommended 7...dxe6, which will inevitably equalize for Black, but I prefer to complicate matters and get a typical Benko structure. }
7... fxe6 { Following the old principles, we capture towards the centre. } 8.
Nc3
{ This is played even less than 8. e5 but is the better way to go for White as he defends the pawn without creating any more weakness.   A fun fact is that Bluebaum @@StartBracket@@now a strong GM@@EndBracket@@ handled the Black side once in this position when his rating was only 1900. Despite that fact, the future GM found the correct move. }
8... Nc6 { Eyeing the sensitive d4 square. } 9. Bxc4 Nd4
{ Once more this knight leap is favourable to us as after  10.Nxd4?  cxd4  Black wins a free pawn on e4. }
10. Qd3 { This move serves both purposes of defending f3 and e4. } 10... Rc8
{ We are setting White a sneaky and hard-to-spot trap. It's up to our opponent whether he generously accepts the poisoned gift. }
11. O-O { Declining the offer is better but doesn't trouble us either. } 11...
Qc7
{ This typical move dissuades  12.Nxd4?  as after  12...cxd4  13.Qxd4  Qxc4  Black wins material. }
12. b3 { White is again threatening Nxd4, so we must act immediately. } 12...
Nxf3+
{ Initially I analyzed  12...a6!?  which is the top engine suggestion and leads to a complicated position in which White doesn't necessarily stand worse and Black need to play with strong accuracy just to stay in the game.  I believe the text move is both easier to learn and easier to play. }
13. Qxf3 Bd6
{ This is the typical idea in this structure: manoeuver the bishop to e5 where it will exert powerful pressure on White's position. }
14. Qh3 { This is the best way to protect h2. } 14... Be5
{ The position is highly unclear and in my opinion, Black has easier play. Don't ask me why Black always has easier play, because I always want you to have it! We have a straightforward plan to improve our position with O-O, Bc6 and Qb7.   Note that sometimes if Bxc3 followed by Nxe4 give us a 'free' pawn we shouldn't take it until there is no risk regarding White's bishop pair. Personally, I wouldn't be eager to win a pawn in that fashion. }
