{ Blocking the e-file. Now White has two moves. } 11. Qe4
{ An interesting attempt. } 11... Nb6
{ Protecting the rook. The reason for choosing this square instead of c7 is that White no longer has the annoying idea of Bf4-c7. }
12. Re1 { Now we should free ourselves from the pin with } 12... d5 13. Qe3 Qd7
{ Securing the c6 square for the knight. } 14. Qxc5 Nc6
{ We will play O-O next, with an equal but not necessarily drawish position due to the imbalance in pawn structures. Our d-pawn can turn into a weakness, but don't forget it's a passed pawn. }
