[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poisonous Gift: 4. c4"]
[Black "5. a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c4
{ This move is very interesting. White offers a pawn with the hope that he will regain it later. For example, if we grab the offer with  4...bxc4?!  White will simply continue with  5.Nc3  with e4 and Bxc4 to follow.   I would love to recommend  4...b4  as after  5.a4  we would find ourselves transposed to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  and thus cut down the study time. Unfortunately, White has the nasty reply  5.a3!  when I think White's chances are slightly better due to the prospect on the a-file. }
4... Bb7
{ We keep the tension and take aim at the d5-pawn. Actually, now we have transposed into a sideline of the 'real' Benko Gambit:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bb7  .  This is thoroughly covered in Lifetime Repertoires: Benko Gambit. To avoid overlap, I've analysed different replies in the main lines. I will make sure that you will be able to see both my and Swapnil's recommendations.   Note that  5.Bg5  transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bb7  5.c4  ,  a line covered later in this course. }
5. a4
{ We should congratulate White for being so smart: he has managed to move-ordered us out of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  b4  5.c4  variation, where our choice is to break immediately with  5...e6  instead of  5...Bb7    Nevertheless, our position is still fully playable and we will use different plans. The b7-bishop is very passive but quite often we will re-route it through the c8 square.   Also, White's tricky move order has its own drawback, which we will exploit with the equally nasty check. }
5... Qa5+
{ A check first to force White's bishop to the clumsy d2-square where it will obstruct the knight. White will lose some more tempi to develop, and that compensates for the time we need to solve the problem regarding the b7-bishop. Note that sometimes b3+ can be a pretty irritating check.   Now  6.Bd2  is forced, as  6.Nbd2?  loses a pawn to the simple  6...bxc4  . }
6. Bd2 b4
{ This is also forced. Now we will take a look at two of White's most popular choices. }
7. Bg5
{ White accepts the fact that his bishop is badly placed and spends another tempo to free the d2 square for the knight. Here the overwhelmingly popular move is  7...d6  ,  as recommended in Lifetime Repertoires: Benko Gambit but I like a rarer but perfectly sound 'attack the attacker' approach. }
7... Ne4 { White has to make a decision regarding the g5-bishop. } 8. Bf4
{ 8.Bh4  is still met with  8...d6  followed by Nd7 and g6, while the tempting Alpha-Zero's  8.h4!?  is countered by  8...Nxg5  9.hxg5  g6!  and the bishop will be very active on g7.   We should delay kingside castling with the h-file opened and our king is safe in the centre. }
8... d6 9. Nbd2 { White offer the exchange of our strong knight } 9... Nxd2 10.
Qxd2
{ In the only game that reached this position, Black played the inferior 10...g6. However, there is a much more powerful shot available. }
10... e5
{ The situation in the centre allows us to execute this break, gaining space for a potential kingside offensive. As if White retreats his bishop we will have a dangerous initiative on the kingside, taking en passant is the only way to proceed. }
11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Ng5 { Threatening the e6-pawn. } 12... e5
{ Moving forward is the best option, as we shouldn't touch our king just yet. }
13. Bg3 Be7
{ Our idea is to play Nc6-d4 and O-O when we will dominate the board. } 14. Ne6
{ White's only try to complicate life. g7 is under fire, but we continue to react in a cool fashion. }
14... Kf7 { All of a sudden, the knight on e6 has no good square. } 15. Ng5+
{ The knight is forced to move back. } 15... Bxg5 16. Qxg5 b3+
{ Finally, one of the points behind our tricky Qa5+ appears on the board. } 17.
Qd2 Nc6
{ White has many weaknesses, notably the c4-pawn and the d4 square. Both of White's bishops are horrendously passive. Black may continue with Rhd8, Nb4 or even h5-h4. }
*

