{ We keep the tension and take aim at the d5-pawn. Actually, now we have transposed into a sideline of the 'real' Benko Gambit:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Bb7  .  This is thoroughly covered in Lifetime Repertoires: Benko Gambit. To avoid overlap, I've analysed different replies in the main lines. I will make sure that you will be able to see both my and Swapnil's recommendations.   Note that  5.Bg5  transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bg5  Bb7  5.c4  ,  a line covered later in this course. }
5. a4
{ We should congratulate White for being so smart: he has managed to move-ordered us out of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  b4  5.c4  variation, where our choice is to break immediately with  5...e6  instead of  5...Bb7    Nevertheless, our position is still fully playable and we will use different plans. The b7-bishop is very passive but quite often we will re-route it through the c8 square.   Also, White's tricky move order has its own drawback, which we will exploit with the equally nasty check. }
5... Qa5+
{ A check first to force White's bishop to the clumsy d2-square where it will obstruct the knight. White will lose some more tempi to develop, and that compensates for the time we need to solve the problem regarding the b7-bishop. Note that sometimes b3+ can be a pretty irritating check.   Now  6.Bd2  is forced, as  6.Nbd2?  loses a pawn to the simple  6...bxc4  . }
6. Bd2 b4
{ This is also forced. Now we will take a look at two of White's most popular choices. }
7. Qc2
{ This is the most popular move. White is simply preparing e4 to take over the centre. }
7... d6
{ Bareev played  7...g6  , but we have a different intention, which will soon be revealed. }
8. e4 e5
{ This move is pretty rare, but it has the idea of blocking the centre and slowly organize play on the kingside. Other moves are also possible, but in my opinion, Black has to break with either e5 or e6 at some point in this structure.   As after e6 White can simply keep the tension, an immediate e5 is logical. We are aiming for a King's Indian structure with the queenside firmly blocked, so we can focus on the other wing.   Swapnil's course contains  8...Nbd7  , which is not inferior by any means and is a line in which he has a lot of experience. But as mentioned before, I always prefer to go for the less or not explored road whenever possible. }
9. dxe6
{ Playing like this is not advised at all for White, but an IM once played it. }
9... fxe6 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Ng5
{ 11.O-O  O-O-O  is also bad for White due to his lack of control in the centre. }
11... Nd4
{ Black has a significant advantage due to his big knight and far more active pieces. }
