9. Be2 { White's simple approach is not so critical. } 9... g6 10. O-O Bg7
{ We are still following our standard plan. } 11. Ne1 Nbd7
{ Here White must decide whether he wish to break with f4. } 12. b3
{ White decide to take more time to manoeuver, but now we can seize the initiative on the kingside. }
12... Qd8 { First, bring the queen back just in case. } 13. Be3 h5
{ This creative advance got the approval of my silicon friends. Our idea is to exchange the dark-squared bishop with Bh6, or with Nh7, h4 followed by Bf6, clamping on the dark squares. }
14. Bg5
{ White immediately takes advantage of our last move, but the pin is nothing to worry about. }
14... Qe7 { Paving the way for queenside castling. } 15. Nd2 Bh6
{ And get rid of the annoying bishop! } 16. Bxh6 Rxh6 17. Nd3 g5
{ Black fearlessly rushes his kingside pawns forward, and in the next few moves, we are going to bring all pieces to the party. After O-O-O Black's king will be away from any danger while its counterpart will come under a fierce attack.   The engine is well-known to mishandle this kind of blocked position, so I would be brave and say that Black is strategically dominating here, an opinion that the engine doesn't share. }
