[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Venomous Gambit: 4. e4!?"]
[Black "4. e4 Nxe4 5. Bxb5??"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. e4
{ In this chapter, I'm going to cover this super-venomous gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn for lightning-fast development and a dangerous initiative.   Quite often, the first player can generate a quick attack along the e-file and mate us there. I cover this variation in-depth because it's recommended by my compatriot, GM Le in his Lifetime Repertoires: London System.   We should be very careful to avoid an immediate disaster! }
4... Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn isn't just a principled decision: it's forced to avoid an early loss! What's our knight doing there on f6, if we cannot capture the e4-pawn?   At this point, White has several continuations:  5.Bd3!  is the best and most dangerous continuation, but we will first examine the alternatives,  5.Nc3  and  5.Nbd2  . }
5. Bxb5 { Of course loses to a simple fork. } 5... Qa5+
{ And White will find himself a piece down. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Venomous Gambit: 4. e4!?"]
[Black "4. e4 Nxe4 5. Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. e4
{ In this chapter, I'm going to cover this super-venomous gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn for lightning-fast development and a dangerous initiative.   Quite often, the first player can generate a quick attack along the e-file and mate us there. I cover this variation in-depth because it's recommended by my compatriot, GM Le in his Lifetime Repertoires: London System.   We should be very careful to avoid an immediate disaster! }
4... Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn isn't just a principled decision: it's forced to avoid an early loss! What's our knight doing there on f6, if we cannot capture the e4-pawn?   At this point, White has several continuations:  5.Bd3!  is the best and most dangerous continuation, but we will first examine the alternatives,  5.Nc3  and  5.Nbd2  . }
5. Nc3
{ A rare sideline that caught my attention because it's among the engine suggestions. White's idea is to remove our centralized knight and open the b-file for his rook. The b5-pawn is especially vulnerable because White can attack it with a2-a4, c2-c4 and the bishop on f1 is also taking aim. }
5... Nxc3
{ There's no reason to refrain from this exchange.  5...Qa5  is also interesting, but we aren't going after some material just to be get mated later, right? }
6. bxc3 g6
{ Simple and effective. We don't waste time defending the b5-pawn, but instead, speed up our development.  6...a6  and  6...Qa5  are definitely playable, and indeed they are appealing to the engine.   However, I decided against them because, in practice, it's far from trivial to defend against White's initiative, no matter how many pawns you are up. Moreover, the engine is giving the infamous zero trilogies @@StartBracket@@0.00 evaluation@@EndBracket@@, which means that Black should have no advantage even with engine-like defending and suffering.   After giving back the b5-pawn, we will have a pleasant middlegame ahead because of White's ruined structure. }
7. Bxb5 Bg7
{ The c3-pawn is indeed hanging, but it's of little value anyway, so White can even ignore it. }
8. Bd2 { However, defending the pawn is also possible. } 8... Na6
{ A nice and typical manoeuver to remember. The knight is heading for c7 in order to target the d5-pawn. }
9. O-O Nc7
{ White must make a critical decision regarding the future of the bishop. } 10.
Bc4 { Protecting the c4-pawn in a modest fashion. } 10... d6
{ In this type of structure we should be aware of White's d6 break; for example,  10...O-O  11.d6!  exd6  12.Bg5!  Bf6  13.Qxd6  leaves White at least slightly better with a positional bind. }
11. Re1 O-O 12. Bg5
{ The pressure on e7 looks threatening, but in fact, we can reply with a simple and effective move. }
12... Bf6 { Neutralizing the g5-bishop. } 13. Bxf6 exf6
{ Both sides have doubled pawns, but Black's f-pawns are more useful than White's c-pawns because they act as a cover for Black's king and control several important squares. White's main trump is the d5-pawn that restricts Black's minor pieces, but it can easily become a weakness later.   Overall, the position is balanced @@StartBracket@@ but by no means drawish@@EndBracket@@ with chances for both sides to outplay their opponent in the coming fight. }
*

