{ Simple and effective. We don't waste time defending the b5-pawn, but instead, speed up our development.  6...a6  and  6...Qa5  are definitely playable, and indeed they are appealing to the engine.   However, I decided against them because, in practice, it's far from trivial to defend against White's initiative, no matter how many pawns you are up. Moreover, the engine is giving the infamous zero trilogies @@StartBracket@@0.00 evaluation@@EndBracket@@, which means that Black should have no advantage even with engine-like defending and suffering.   After giving back the b5-pawn, we will have a pleasant middlegame ahead because of White's ruined structure. }
7. Bxb5 Bg7
{ The c3-pawn is indeed hanging, but it's of little value anyway, so White can even ignore it. }
8. Bd2 { However, defending the pawn is also possible. } 8... Na6
{ A nice and typical manoeuver to remember. The knight is heading for c7 in order to target the d5-pawn. }
9. O-O Nc7
{ White must make a critical decision regarding the future of the bishop. } 10.
c4
{ A brave exchange sacrifice in order to gain complete control of the dark squares. }
10... Nxb5
{ The engine also gives  10...Bxa1  , but after  11.Qxa1  f6  12.Ba5!  Black is boxed in with no counterplay in sight. An exchange is an exchange, but in that event, the rook isn't necessarily stronger than the bishop. }
11. cxb5 a6
{ 11...Bxa1  is unappealing to my eye again, this time due to  12.Qxa1  f6  13.Bh6!  when the engine's suggestion of  13...d6  followed by Kd7 isn't to everybody's taste. With the text move, Black strives to open the queenside and the position in general as we have the bishop pair. White's queenside is vulnerable after the a-file is opened. }
12. b6 { White desperately tries to close the a-file. } 12... Qxb6 13. Rb1 Qc7
{ Nevertheless, Black is still clearly better with two dominating bishops against White's weak pawns on a2 and d5. They are young children crying for help but receive nothing. Oh, and Black is a pawn up. }
14. Re1 d6 15. Qe2
{ 15.Bg5  can be met with either the weakening  15...f6!?  16.Bf4  O-O  with a complicated position.   Or @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/2q1ppbp/p2p2p1/2pP2B1/8/5N2/P1P2PPP/1R1QR1K1 b kq - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...O-O  16.Rxe7  Qa5!  with a slight initiative. With the text move, White lines up on the e-file. He must be expecting us to spend a few tempi guarding the e7-pawn, but in reality, this is the appropriate moment to give it back. }
15... O-O
{ Black is a pawn up for so long, forcing White to spend his energies pressuring it. Then, we give it away for free. Or it is free? }
16. Qxe7 Qxe7 17. Rxe7 Bf5
{ Black retains dangerous pressure against White's queenside, and therefore stands clearly better. }
