6. bxc3 g6
{ Simple and effective. We don't waste time defending the b5-pawn, but instead, speed up our development.  6...a6  and  6...Qa5  are definitely playable, and indeed they are appealing to the engine.   However, I decided against them because, in practice, it's far from trivial to defend against White's initiative, no matter how many pawns you are up. Moreover, the engine is giving the infamous zero trilogies @@StartBracket@@0.00 evaluation@@EndBracket@@, which means that Black should have no advantage even with engine-like defending and suffering.   After giving back the b5-pawn, we will have a pleasant middlegame ahead because of White's ruined structure. }
7. Bxb5 Bg7
{ The c3-pawn is indeed hanging, but it's of little value anyway, so White can even ignore it. }
8. O-O { Ignoring the c3-pawn is the best way to continue. } 8... O-O
{ The pawn is poisoned:  8...Bxc3?  9.Bh6!  and our king is terribly stuck in the middle of the board, something which the exchange cannot make up for. }
9. Rb1 { The rook runs away from the fire on the long diagonal. } 9... d6
{ Whenever we can play d6,  it's usually best to play it, not allowing White to execute that break himself. Here,  9...Bxc3?  would be a mistake due to  10.d6!  e6  11.Bh6!  removing our dark-square defender.  11...Bg7  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.Ne5!  with a significant advantage for White. }
10. c4
{ Solidifying the position of the b5-bishop and preventing any Bxc3 possibility. However, White's last move also limits the air of the b5-bishop. }
10... Qa5
{ Excellent chess! Black reveals the drawback of 10. c4 with a queen sortie, with the seemingly clear intention of capturing on a2.   While it's true that in some lines we can capture it, the main point behind  10...Qa5  is that the a4-square is now under our control, and ...a6 will leave White's bishop dangerously short of squares. }
11. Rb3
{ White definitely has some compensation after  11.Bd2  Qxa2  , but it's insufficient and Black should be better with correct play.   With the text move, White intends to meet @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/p3ppbp/3p2p1/qBpP4/2P5/1R3N2/P1P2PPP/2BQ1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  with  12.Ra3  ,  when a retreat of the queen is 'inevitable'. The b5-pawn would no longer be hanging, as the a6-pawn would be pinned to the rook. I've just written it myself, but is a retreat of the queen really forced? }
11... a6 12. Ra3 Qxa3
{ The answer is no! Black can, and should bravely give up the queen for just a rook and a bishop. In return, we will have overwhelming control of the queenside. This is a purely positional sacrifice, so there won't be checkmate or immediate material gain for us, but White is already on the defensive side. }
13. Bxa3 axb5 { The a3-bishop is hanging. } 14. Bc1
{ The only move as  14.Qc1?  bxc4!  is very good for Black. } 14... b4
{ The c4-pawn can be captured later, in a more favourable way. Black is slightly better here, and on the next move, we will capture on a2 when the material equilibrium is already reached. }
