1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. e4
{ In this chapter, I'm going to cover this super-venomous gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn for lightning-fast development and a dangerous initiative.   Quite often, the first player can generate a quick attack along the e-file and mate us there. I cover this variation in-depth because it's recommended by my compatriot, GM Le in his Lifetime Repertoires: London System.   We should be very careful to avoid an immediate disaster! }
4... Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn isn't just a principled decision: it's forced to avoid an early loss! What's our knight doing there on f6, if we cannot capture the e4-pawn?   At this point, White has several continuations:  5.Bd3!  is the best and most dangerous continuation, but we will first examine the alternatives,  5.Nc3  and  5.Nbd2  . }
5. Nbd2
{ Another dangerous sideline that is worth analyzing. White wants to exchange a pair of knights without weakening his structure. Moreover, after  5...Nxd2  White would be able to develop a piece on the d2 square, even though it's arguably not an ideal one. If you have studied everything my course until here, you won't be surprised to hear that I opt against the natural knight exchange, and for something far more weird-looking and original. }
5... Nd6
{ Initially, I went for  5...Nf6!?  instead, but after  6.Bxb5  Nxd5  7.Nc4  e6  8.Ng5!  White's compensation is really apparent and a mistake can lead to our demise.  With the text move, Black puts the knight on the strange-looking d6 square where it blocks the d-pawn. However, it controls many key squares, protecting the b5-pawn and is a useful blockader on the d-file. In the future, we may relocate it with Nf5-d4, but very often it's perfectly placed on its current square. We've used 3 out of 5 moves with the knight, but the d2-knight is also blocking his pieces, so our development disadvantage shouldn't be so serious. }
6. c4
{ White targets the b5-pawn in a different manner. However, in comparison to 6. a4, this time we can leave the pawn where it is as cxb5 is a positionally undesirable capture.   Firstly, I will show you what will happen if we play the cooperative  6...bxc4?!  , and then move on to my recommendation,  6...g6! }
6... g6
{ My preference. Black offers the b5-pawn for a quick fianchetto and intends a6 later, with Benko-like pressure down the queenside files. }
7. b4
{ Setting the board on fire. The engine regards this as the best move for White, but I will only devote some light coverage to this move as it's highly unlikely that White can reach this far. }
7... Bg7
{ Temporarily ignores all the chaos happening on the queenside and targets the a1-rook. This is the best move, as  7...cxb4?  allows  8.Bb2!  when Black is forced to play either the sad  8...Rg8  or weakening  8...f6 }
8. cxb5
{ A highly imaginative idea. White sacrifices a whole rook to get his pawn majority rolling. Even though White's centre will look very appealing, a rook is a rook and this concept is, unfortunately, refuted. }
8... Bxa1 { Grabbing the rook is the principled and correct option. } 9. bxc5
Nb7 { Hitting the c5-pawn. } 10. Nb3 Bc3+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Qc7
{ Black is completely winning. Next move, we might even sacrifice the knight for the dangerous c5-pawn. }
