{ My preference. Black offers the b5-pawn for a quick fianchetto and intends a6 later, with Benko-like pressure down the queenside files. }
7. b4
{ Setting the board on fire. The engine regards this as the best move for White, but I will only devote some light coverage to this move as it's highly unlikely that White can reach this far. }
7... Bg7
{ Temporarily ignores all the chaos happening on the queenside and targets the a1-rook. This is the best move, as  7...cxb4?  allows  8.Bb2!  when Black is forced to play either the sad  8...Rg8  or weakening  8...f6  . }
8. bxc5
{ After examining the disastrous consequences to the alternatives, it's time to turn our attention to the text move, which is the only move not to lose. White gives up the exchange in order to seize a dangerous initiative. }
8... Nb7
{ 8...Bxa1  is a viable alternative, but White can maintain the balance with accurate play and in this course, I've tried to avoid scenarios when we are material up but has to defend against White's dangerous initiative. The text is a much more reliable choice. The resulting positions are easy to handle. }
9. Rb1
{ The only way to maintain material balance.  9.Ba3?!  insists on the exchange sacrifice, but we have the nice touch  9...b4!  available, forcing the bishop to the b4 square. After  10.Bxb4  Na6!  11.a3  Alternatives are even worse.  11...Naxc5  Black is clearly better with a powerful bishop on the long diagonal and the c5-knight. The backward c4-pawn is a long-term weakness for White. }
9... Nxc5
{ Removing the cramping pawn. White has two ways to recapture on b5. } 10. cxb5
{ White frees the c4-square for the minor pieces and hints at the possibility of creating a passed pawn on the queenside in the future. On the other hand, the d5-pawn is weakened and while the queenside pawn majority might be dangerous in the endgame, in the middlegame Black can target them with Qa5.   10.Rxb5  is an obvious alternative. After  10...d6  11.Bb2  Bxb2  12.Rxb2  e5!  Black's position is excellent.  13.dxe6  is positionally forced @@StartBracket@@otherwise Black's structure is clearly superior and we can build up on the kingside@@EndBracket@@ when we can consider between the normal  13...Bxe6  with a satisfactory position or the cold-blooded  13...Qf6!?  with the point that  14.exf7+?  Kxf7  gives Black a deadly attack with Re8+ and Bf5 coming. Note that the b2-rook is hanging, too. }
10... d6 { Preventing White to play d6 himself. } 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Nc4 Nbd7
{ Preparing both Nb6 and Nf6. } 13. O-O O-O 14. Bb2
{ Exchanging the g7-bishop, but it's striking at thin air anyway. } 14... Bxb2
15. Rxb2 Nb6
{ The key idea. Black forces the exchange on b6 in order to open the a-file. }
16. Nxb6 { 16.Ne3  Ne4!  is uncomfortable for White. } 16... axb6
{ Black's position is surely easier to play. We have no weakness, the a-file and a dream knight on c5. White will suffer from the chronic problem of the a-pawn, even though for now Black is just slightly better. Next, we will continue with Ra4/Ra3 and prepare the e6 break which will relieve our bishop. }
