{ My preference. Black offers the b5-pawn for a quick fianchetto and intends a6 later, with Benko-like pressure down the queenside files. }
7. cxb5 { Critical, but not best. } 7... a6 { Opening up the queenside. } 8.
Nb3 { This paradoxical move is the top engine suggestion. } 8... Bg7
{ Leaving the pawn where it is. The initiative is of much greater importance than a mere pawn. Moreover, we can regain the b5-pawn at will. }
9. Nxc5
{ White is currently a pawn up, but his whole queenside is under huge pressure. }
9... O-O
{ 9...axb5  10.Be2  O-O  is another move-order, but the used move order gives White more chances to go wrong. }
10. Nxa6 { Too greedy. } 10... Nxa6 11. bxa6 Bxa6 12. Bxa6
{ 12....Rxa6  would give Black just enough compensation, but we want more. }
12... Qa5+
{ A standard resource. Black wants to capture the bishop with the queen in order to prevent White from castling. }
13. Qd2 { 13.Bd2  Qxa6-+  is even worse. } 13... Qxa6 14. Qe2
{ Offering a queen exchange in order to reduce Black's attacking potential. }
14... Qa5+
{ Black is on top after capturing the d5-pawn. Note that  15.Qd2?  aiming for repetition would be a mistake due to  15...Qxd2+  16.Kxd2  Nc4+  with a devastating attack. }
