[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. e4
{ In this chapter, I'm going to cover this super-venomous gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn for lightning-fast development and a dangerous initiative.   Quite often, the first player can generate a quick attack along the e-file and mate us there. I cover this variation in-depth because it's recommended by my compatriot, GM Le in his Lifetime Repertoires: London System.   We should be very careful to avoid an immediate disaster! }
4... Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn isn't just a principled decision: it's forced to avoid an early loss! What's our knight doing there on f6, if we cannot capture the e4-pawn?   At this point, White has several continuations:  5.Bd3!  is the best and most dangerous continuation, but we will first examine the alternatives,  5.Nc3  and  5.Nbd2  . }
5. Bd3
{ The main idea behind White's concept. White hits our knight and gains a useful tempo for development. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...Nd6  is the most principled move, hanging on to the pawn. However, the way Le Quang Liem convincingly crushed Firouzja in this line left such a strong impression on me that I decide to avoid this double-edged line altogether.   The text move is logical and based on a sound positional foundation. Even though our knight is forced to move back and forth, so is White's bishop. In the middlegame, most likely at some point, White must move his b5-bishop again, so we aren't losing time at all. After giving up the pawn, our developing moves will be easy to make as there aren't so many concrete details to remember. However, after the opening, we can be ensured of a lively middlegame because of the imbalance in pawn structures. }
6. Bxb5 g6
{ The bishop is best placed on g7, where it can exert its influence on the long diagonal. }
7. O-O Bg7
{ We've reached a tabiya of the whole 5. Bd3 variation. White has several options from this point, but none of them can question the soundness of my recommendation. }
8. d6
{ The most ambitious continuation. White takes advantage of the fact that we cannot play d6 yet and seizes the opportunity to do so. Now, we must do something about the pawn. }
8... e6
{ 9...exd6??  is obviously not possible due to  10.Re1+  and our king is helpless in the centre.   However,  9...O-O!?  is a viable option, intending  10.dxe7  Qxe7  11.Nc3  Bb7  with an unclear position.  With the text move, Black closes the centre and intends to play around the d6-pawn later. True, some kingside dark squares are weakened, but our Dragon bishop is there to take care. If it goes off the board then our position would be treacherous, but I don't see any way for White to achieve this goal any time soon. }
9. Nc3 { The main option which I will focus on. } 9... O-O 10. Be3
{ Hitting the c5-pawn. } 10... Qb6
{ Defending the c5-pawn. This move looks rather strange as Black voluntarily puts the queen into a pin, but it turns out that tactics work for Black. If it works, it works, despite the cavalier appearance. }
11. b4 { Pressuring the c5-pawn in the most direct way. } 11... Na6
{ The only way to defend the pawn. If White wishes so, he can 'win' a pawn at the cost of the bishop pair, but there is another dangerous alternative. }
12. bxc5 Nxc5 13. Ne5
{ 13.Rb1  Ng4!  is a nice tactical sequence, after which Black stands no worse in the tactical melee, as you can check yourself. But there is no way I will dive deep into a 13th move sideline like this, as it would be impractical and unnecessary. }
13... Nd5
{ This is the position mentioned in the last line, with the tiny difference is that White has an extra a-pawn. }
14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qxd5
{ 15.Nxf7!?  is a funky tactical trick. After  15...Rxf7  16.Qxd5  Qxb5  17.Qxa8  we have the resource  17...Qb7!  forcing the exchange of queens, resulting in an approximately equal but unbalanced endgame. The battle between White's rook and a pawn versus our minor pieces will be very exciting! The text move requires no explanation: after all, what can be more natural than capturing a hanging piece? }
15... Qxb5 16. Qxa8
{ 16.Rab1!?  is a tricky alternative. We should react with the intermezzo  16...Bb7!  , with a complicated endgame after  17.Rxb5  Bxd5  18.Rxc5  Bxa2  19.Nxd7  Rfd8  .  White's d-pawn is dangerous, but our bishop pair and passed a-pawn shouldn't be underestimated either. }
16... Bxe5
{ The series of captures has ended, and Black emerges with 2 minor pieces for a rook and a pawn. However, our pieces are so strong that there is only a move for White to maintain the balance. }
17. Qd5
{ Among other moves,  17.Rad1?  loses to  17...Bb7  18.Qxa7  Qc6-+  with a winning positional advantage. }
17... Bxa1 18. Rxa1
{ White will definitely capture on c5 next, but how can we make this under favourable conditions for us? }
18... Qb2
{ 18...Re8  is also possible, but defending a pawn down endgame isn't my taste. With the text move, we get out of the pin on the 5th rank while hitting the rook. White should be lost, if not for a spectacular resource. }
19. Bd4
{ Bravo! White simultaneously defends the rook, hitting the queen while keeping the pressure on the knight. }
19... Qxc2 20. Bxc5 Qc3
{ The long diagonal is slightly vulnerable, so our queen must cover it. } 21.
Bd4 { Is met with the cool } 21... Bb7
{ When Black has secured equality as a queen exchange is highly probable. Note that  22.Qe5  can be met by  22...f6  23.Qf4  Qc6  ,  when it's White's turn to be careful. }
*

