6. Bxb5 g6
{ The bishop is best placed on g7, where it can exert its influence on the long diagonal. }
7. O-O Bg7
{ We've reached a tabiya of the whole 5. Bd3 variation. White has several options from this point, but none of them can question the soundness of my recommendation. }
8. d6
{ The most ambitious continuation. White takes advantage of the fact that we cannot play d6 yet and seizes the opportunity to do so. Now, we must do something about the pawn. }
8... e6
{ 9...exd6??  is obviously not possible due to  10.Re1+  and our king is helpless in the centre.   However,  9...O-O!?  is a viable option, intending  10.dxe7  Qxe7  11.Nc3  Bb7  with an unclear position.  With the text move, Black closes the centre and intends to play around the d6-pawn later. True, some kingside dark squares are weakened, but our Dragon bishop is there to take care. If it goes off the board then our position would be treacherous, but I don't see any way for White to achieve this goal any time soon. }
9. Nc3 { The main option which I will focus on. } 9... O-O 10. Be3 Qb6
{ Defending the c5-pawn. This move looks rather strange as Black voluntarily puts the queen into a pin, but it turns out that tactics work for Black. If it works, it works, despite the cavalier appearance. }
