{ The only way to defend the pawn. If White wishes so, he can 'win' a pawn at the cost of the bishop pair, but there is another dangerous alternative. }
12. Bxa6 { White decides to go for a pawn. } 12... Qxa6 13. Bxc5 Nh5
{ Hitting the c3-knight. } 14. Qd2 Qc4 15. Bd4
{ White tries to exchange the bishops in order to relieve the pressure. } 15...
f6
{ No, said Black, even at the cost of the temporary activity of the bishop. }
16. Qe3 e5
{ Black has full compensation for the missing pawn. The position is complicated and highly original. Next, Black will play on the kingside with Nf4, Bb7 and a kingside offensive with f5/g5.  Conclusion: GM Le Quang Liem's 4. e4!? is, as the chapter's title suggests, a venomous sideline which we should treat with respect. 4...Nxe4 is the only move, after which we reach a branching point. First, I analyzed the rather provocative knight moves 5. Nbd2 and 5. Nc3. However, I believe 5. Bd3! is the most critical move theoretically. I recommend you to play 5...Nf6!?, an original sideline that seems to be working. In some lines, we will be forced to sacrifice a pawn or two, but you can be guaranteed that our compensation is objectively sufficient and White will face a difficult task in practice. This is one of the most enjoyable chapters for me to analyze, and I hope you will, too! }
