{ After examining a bunch of White's fourth moves, finally, we come to the absolute main line, which is played roughly two more times than the second most popular move, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  .  White's intention is to double Black's pawns with Bxf6. This threat was and is considered so dangerous that Black's most popular moves are  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP2B1/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qb6  and  4...Ne4  ,  refusing to allow White to execute his threat. This move has been played by famous names such as Le Quang Liem, Boris Gelfand, Radjabov, Kramnik versus his rival Topalov, Wesley So and even Garry Kasparov. Additionally, this was recommended in Axel Smith's book e3 Poison. Against this bishop sortie, I propose an uncommon reply which was championed by creative English figures such as Hodgson and Miles. }
4... Bb7
{ We ignore White's threat and counter it with our own attack on the d5 pawn! Obviously  5.Bxf6  is critical,   but we will first look at  5.c4  . }
5. c4
{ White doesn't want to part with the bishop just yet. Actually, this transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bb7  5.Bg5  , which is a more common move order to get here. }
5... Ne4
{ We exploit White's delay and gain a tempo on the bishop. Actually, with a smart move-order, we have tricked White into an inferior version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP2B1/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ne4  ,  when after  5.Bh4  Bb7  or  5.Bf4  Bb7  6.a4!  would have given White the advantage, as confirmed in practice. }
6. Nc3
{ This is only behind  6.Bf4  in popularity. White gives up the bishop pair to speed up his development, but we have a nice trick. }
6... Nxg5 7. Nxg5 e6
{ This small tactic is the key. The g5-knight is now hanging. } 8. Qd2
{ The safest choice, but now we can start harassing White's pieces with } 8...
b4 9. Nce4 Be7 10. h4
{ Maintaining the knight on g5. Now, we should develop our own knight with }
10... exd5 11. cxd5 d6 { The knight is heading for the juicy e5 square. } 12.
Ng3 Nd7 13. Nf5
{ This may look dangerous, but Black has nothing to worry about after the simple }
13... O-O
{ With a complicated position. White's kingside pressure hasn't given him anything concrete yet, while Black's pieces are very flexible. The d5 pawn will be a permanent headache for White. }
