{ White doesn't want to part with the bishop just yet. Actually, this transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bb7  5.Bg5  , which is a more common move order to get here. }
5... Ne4
{ We exploit White's delay and gain a tempo on the bishop. Actually, with a smart move-order, we have tricked White into an inferior version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP2B1/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ne4  ,  when after  5.Bh4  Bb7  or  5.Bf4  Bb7  6.a4!  would have given White the advantage, as confirmed in practice. }
6. h4
{ This unplayed Alpha-Zero advance contains a lot of venoms. The position resembles the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/6B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Ne4  3.h4!?  variation in the Trompowsky, but here we already generated a lot of pressure on White's centre.   At this point, I will offer two choices.  6...g6  is the simpler option and my main recommendation, while  6...h6!?  leads to a piece sacrifice that is riskier and with engine-like play White will emerge better. Nevertheless, you can try this at least once, especially considering the fact that your opponent is likely to be caught off-guard from the first moves. }
6... h6 { We kick the bishop away first, gaining a useful tempo. } 7. Bf4 Qa5+
{ White has several ways to block the check. } 8. Nbd2
{ 8.Nc3!?  is better, but  @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pb1pppp1/7p/qppP4/2P1nB1P/5N2/PP2PPP1/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2!  is probably best and casts doubt on Black's play. After  8...Nxd2  9.Nbxd2  bxc4  10.e4!  White has a positional advantage as our light-square bishop is terribly bad. But  @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pb1pppp1/7p/qppP4/2P1n2P/5N2/PP1BPPP1/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qc7!?  is an interesting idea which you can explore if you wish to. I choose the text move for entertainment purposes, as the coming sequence is so crazy that I believe you shouldn't miss it. }
8... bxc4 9. b4
{ The only move for White to stay in the game.  9...Qxb4?  loses to  10.Rb1  so Black is forced to sacrifice a piece for a pawn mass. }
9... cxb4 { One pawn goes... } 10. Nxe4 Qxd5 { ...and another! } 11. Qxd5 Bxd5
12. Ng3 f6
{ Preparing e5. In this peculiar position, both sides have their own chances, and the position can turn to anyone's favour after some inaccuracies. Nevertheless, it's likely that   @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pb1pppp1/7p/qppP4/2P1nB1P/5N2/PP2PPP1/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2!  is a near positional refutation of our play. }
