7. a4
{ White may try a different approach against our b5-pawn, but we react in the same fashion anyway. }
7... Bg7
{ For the sake of initiative, we are willing to give up materials. The next few moves are by no means forced, but they show how can we generate compensation in this position. }
8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 10. Bxb5 Qa5+
{ This key check is needed to drive the knight to the unfavourable c3 square. }
11. Nc3 f5
{ The position is equal according to my beloved silicon friend, but Black's play is undeniably easier as we are the attacking side. The immediate threat is Bxc3+ followed by Qxb5 winning a piece, which is not easy to meet. }
