{ This skewer wins a bishop, but White will try to get to our king as soon as possible. We will need to show creative defending in this fun position. }
14. Qxf5 Rxc4 { It's White's turn to play an only move. } 15. b3
{ Having seen Black's resource of Re4+, it makes sense to drive the rook away first before penetrating with the queen. The question is: where should the rook go? }
15... Rc5
{ For concrete reasons explained later this is the best square. Now White has several queen moves. }
16. Qg4
{ This is the best move for a hidden reason: the queen is controlling the b4 square! You might think that's completely irrelevant, but actually White now has the important resource of c4! which gives him fairly decent compensation for the piece.   On the other hand, the queen doesn't exert pressure on the h4-d8 diagonal as  16.Qg5  does, so Black can initiate the king walk. }
16... Kd8 17. c4
{ As mentioned, without this elegant pawn move White would be dead lost. Now, the position of the first player looks very appealing, but we should keep our calmness and break up White's centre. }
17... e6
{ White's best chance is to sacrifice the impressive pawn centre in order to open some files for his rooks. }
18. O-O
{ 18.d6  Kc8!  completes the king walk, resulting in a winning position for Black as  17.Qg8+  can be met by  17...Qd8 }
18... exd5
{ We have enough pieces around the king to afford to grab this pawn. Both sides are walking on a slippery path with a lot of pitfalls. }
19. Rfd1
{ The only way to keep the attack going as after  19.cxd5  Rxd5  White's initiative fades away. }
19... dxc4 { One more pawn! } 20. bxc4 Rxe5
{ It's this moment that justifies our decision to put the rook on c5 several moves ago. The bridgehead in White's position must be removed even at the cost of the exchange. }
21. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ Black will consolidate with Bc6, Na6 and Kc7 while White doesn't have enough pieces to bring our king any danger. Black is better here. }
