{ This is the first time ever in this course @@StartBracket@@ and at the time of publishing, the only time! @@EndBracket@@ I analyze two different moves at the 21st move! You might call it unhelpful and impractical considering that @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb1ppp1p/8/1ppP1p2/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  is never played in the database and  @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/pb1ppp1p/8/qppPPp2/8/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nc3  is a novelty even in the world of online chess. However, this line is critical to the evaluation of the whole variation, so I made an exception.   21.Nxe5  looks pretty natural, but the text move is the bizarre suggestion of my non-human friends which I don't think any human would have played without their engine's assistance. The idea is to ignore the e5-rook and open the a-file. Many of the following moves are incredibly hard to understand, and I'd suggest you not remember them, but just to enjoy the beauty chess in general and the Spielmann-Indian, in particular, can offer. }
21... Re4
{ I like this rook move as it poses an immediate question to the White queen. }
22. Qg7
{ Again White's only move, although it's not very clear why.  22.Qg8+  Re8!  23.Qxf7  b3!  would have been better for Black as we managed to close the a-file and safeguard our king. }
22... Qb6 { Preparing Qg6 to exchange queens. } 23. Ng5 Qg6
{ Inviting White to head for an endgame. } 24. Qxg6
{ 24.Qf8+  Re8  25.Nxf7+  Kc7  26.Qc5+  Nc6!  results in another sharp struggle. }
24... hxg6 25. Nxe4 Bxe4 26. axb4 Kc7
{ The position is objectively equal, but the material imbalance means that the fight will continue for a long time.    Conclusion for @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb1ppp1p/8/1ppP1p2/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  : This rarely played move unplayed OTB leads to unclear positions. White's pawn duo in the centre might look very aggressive, but it often becomes a weakness instead of a strength. In return, White has a temporary initiative and sometimes he needs to sacrifice material in order to justify the ambition of his 7th move. Even though it's likely that the White player doesn't know any theory at all @@StartBracket@@ in fact, there is no theory to learn besides my course!@@EndBracket@@ I still present the best he can get out of the opening and provide plans for us to continue. Precision, deep understanding and a careful study of the lines guarantee you to get the desired position out of the opening! }
