7. Bxb5
{ After the rollercoaster ride in the  7.e5  variation, we now turn our attention to this pawn grab. White let us capture on e4 for now, but in the future, he will regain that pawn quite easily. A very important resource for Black in this variation is the queen switch Qd8-b6-g6 in order to protect the kingside. }
7... fxe4
{ After the obvious recapture White can either play  8.Nfd2  or  8.Ng5  ,  but it's likely to transpose. }
8. Ng5 { This move order allows White some independent options. } 8... Bg7
{ Attacking the b2-pawn. It's seemingly obvious that White must defend the pawn, but in many lines, he can sacrifice the a1-rook for huge compensation. }
9. c3
{ White blocks the diagonal with a pawn to avoid tactical tricks, but now we can take advantage of White's vulnerable minor pieces and introduce a typical queen maneuver. }
9... Qb6
{ Remember this move, because it will appear again and again in this variation! }
10. Qb3
{ White can defend the bishop, but it's time to go over to the kingside. }
10... Qg6 11. h4
{ The only way to defend.  11.Nh3?!  puts the knight on a super passive square but sets a small trap:  11...Qxg2?  12.Rg1!  and the g7-bishop is lost.   Nevertheless, we have @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/pb1pppbp/6q1/1BpP4/4p3/1QP4N/PP3PPP/RN2K2R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bh6!  and the knight on the rim is really, really dim. Having seen Black's resource of Bh6, it makes sense to insert h4 and h6 so Black no longer owns that possibility. }
11... h6 12. Nh3
{ We cannot capture the g2-pawn, but there is a funky, unusual pawn sacrifice available. }
12... e3
{ 12...O-O  is the soundest move which leads to a dynamic struggle, but I cannot resist creativity.   After the text move, Black is threatening Qxg2 while @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/pb1pppb1/6qp/1BpP4/7P/1QP1p2N/PP3PP1/RN2K2R w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.fxe3  isn't possible due to  13...Qxg2  14.Rg1  Qxh3  and the hidden point is revealed: the e3-pawn is hanging. }
13. O-O
{ The most natural move, but the un-developing  13.Bf1!?  is worth mentioning, as it forces Black to make an un-developing move himself:  13...Bc8!  I warned you about the originality of the course in the title, but probably you didn't imagine that mess, didn't you?   13.Na3!?  is another exciting possibility, preparing O-O-O. }
13... Qe4
{ Hitting both d5 and h4 at once.  13...Rg8!?  and  13...Be5  are possible improvements. }
14. Bc4 Bc8
{ The bishop has no future on b7, so it's time to relocate it away from the long diagonal. The position is extremely unclear and it would take hundreds of lines in order to analyse everything. Creativity is demanded from both sides to handle this peculiar position. }
*

