11... Bd4
{ d4 is normally the best square for the bishop as it exerts influence over the board and cuts White's queen connection with the d5-pawn. }
12. Bc4
{ White has other ways to defend the d5-pawn, but none of them is good enough:  12.Nec3  Qf6!  13.Qd2  Na6!  followed by Nc7 is good for Black.  12.c4?  loses the bishop to  12...a6  and  @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/pb1ppp1p/1q6/1BpP4/P2bN3/8/R1P2PPP/1N1QK2R w Kkq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qh5?  a6!  traps the bishop, as it is pinned to the b1-knight. }
12... Qg6
{ The queen has done its job on the queenside and it's time to cause disharmony on the other wing. }
13. Ng3 h5
{ Brave Harry isn't afraid of going to the battlefield. h5-h4 is in the air and as  14.O-O  ,  the 'castling into it' approach is too risky. White must weaken his kingside with }
14. h4 d6
{ Bringing more pieces into play. Black has fair chances in this complex position with Nd7-e5@@StartBracket@@f6@@EndBracket@@ and even Bc8 as ideas. The king will be safe in the centre, and the rooks may be activated via the b-file and g-file. }
