{ The queen manoeuvre is the hero once again. We hit the bishop and when it retreats Qxb2 wins a whole rook. That's too much a price, so White must keep his bishop on its current square. }
10. Na3
{ Very interesting. White defends the a3-knight by tactical means. The point is that after }
10... Bxb2 11. Nc4
{ The b5 bishop cannot be taken due to the fork on d6. White is threatening both the queen and the bishop, but we can counter with a threat of our own. }
11... Qg6
{ Not the first time we introduced this fine queen sortie! White has two moves now: the gambit  12.O-O!   or the structure-ruining  12.Ned6!?  We will examine the latter first. }
12. Ned6+
{ White accepts that the knight is lost, but he wants to ruin our structure in return. }
12... exd6 13. Nxb2 Qe4+
{ This simple check solves our problem of the passive b7-bishop. } 14. Qe2
Qxe2+ 15. Bxe2 Bxd5
{ Our bishop is finally alive! White gets a temporary initiative now, but with accurate defending, we can equalize. }
16. O-O-O Bxa2 { Securing the potentially dangerous passed a-pawn. } 17. Rxd6
Be6 { The bishop comes back and holds our position together. } 18. Bf3 Nc6 19.
Bxc6
{ 19.Rxc6  dxc6  20.Bxc6+  Ke7  leaves us with a pleasant endgame due to the passed a-pawn, even though it should be drawn with best play from both sides. }
19... dxc6 20. Rxc6 a5 21. Rxc5 a4
{ Our counterplay with the a-pawn will come surprisingly fast, which guarantees us equality. }
