1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Bg5
{ After examining a bunch of White's fourth moves, finally, we come to the absolute main line, which is played roughly two more times than the second most popular move, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  .  White's intention is to double Black's pawns with Bxf6. This threat was and is considered so dangerous that Black's most popular moves are  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP2B1/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qb6  and  4...Ne4  ,  refusing to allow White to execute his threat. This move has been played by famous names such as Le Quang Liem, Boris Gelfand, Radjabov, Kramnik versus his rival Topalov, Wesley So and even Garry Kasparov. Additionally, this was recommended in Axel Smith's book e3 Poison. Against this bishop sortie, I propose an uncommon reply which was championed by creative English figures such as Hodgson and Miles. }
4... Bb7
{ We ignore White's threat and counter it with our own attack on the d5 pawn! Obviously  5.Bxf6  is critical,   but we will first look at  5.c4  . }
5. Bxf6
{ Damaging Black's pawn structure is the start of the mainline of the whole course. Both recaptures have been tested, but I recommend the one which leads to more dynamic and exciting positions. It wasn't mentioned in Smith's book, so I believe it will catch a lot of your opponents out of the book literally! }
5... gxf6
{ There are many advantages of this recapture over  5...exf6    - We will be able to fianchetto the bishop next move   - We capture towards the centre, thus following the principles  - In the future, we can play f5 without worrying about the king's safety   - Our king will be safe in the center most of the time   Of course, this move has its own drawback, namely the weak-looking kingside. The resulting position is extremely complex and sharp as White will try to play against our bishop pair while we strive to open the long diagonals, even at the cost of a pawn or two. You should study carefully in order to understand key strategies/tactics for both sides in this unusual position! At this point  6.e4  is the most popular move which I  analysed extensively, but first, let's look at the restrained  6.e3 }
6. e4
{ White ambitiously seizes space in the centre. This move was played as much as 50 times, but as you can expect from my course, my proposed counter is almost unexplored with just 3 practical examples in the MegaDatabase. As our bishop pair is restricted, we should seek counterplay immediately to avoid being dominated. }
6... f5
{ This move fits the needs of my repertoire: original, sharp and leads to double-edged positions. For a doubled pawn, we managed to  - Soften the defence of the crucial d5 pawn   - Open the long diagonal with tempi   As usual, I want to be honest and don't want to hide any facts. As there is hardly any theory from move 4 onwards, I had to develop them myself. In order to evaluate positions correctly, besides using my own intuition and understanding I often check my recommendations with the engines, as mentioned in the Introduction. Here Stockfish claimed an advantage for White after the greedy   7.exf5  while Leela trusted White to have a slight edge. However, over the time I analyzed the engines started to be less optimistic in White's chances, even though Stockfish still believed that White has a small advantage. In my opinion, Black's disadvantage is only numerically around +0.5 and in practice, he has excellent chances.   To conclude, this line is entirely sound in my view. I understand that some readers aren't satisfied yet, but I hope I can change your judgment with the lines presented. Fun fact: This move is played 2 times in my ChessBase Database, both times by the unknown and unrated player Aleksander Emelyanov, so maybe we can call it the Emelyanov Gambit? }
7. Bxb5
{ After the rollercoaster ride in the  7.e5  variation, we now turn our attention to this pawn grab. White let us capture on e4 for now, but in the future, he will regain that pawn quite easily. A very important resource for Black in this variation is the queen switch Qd8-b6-g6 in order to protect the kingside. }
7... fxe4
{ After the obvious recapture White can either play  8.Nfd2  or  8.Ng5  ,  but it's likely to transpose. }
8. Nfd2 { The knight on d2 allows White to play Nc3 after Black plays Bg7. }
8... Bg7 9. Nxe4
{ This ambitious exchange sacrifice isn't something to underestimate. White's attempt to blow us out of the water is actually very serious. In case we grab the exchange we will lose the dark-square bishop, our king's chief defender. Also, White's pieces will come to life and our king will be in trouble. While objectively we can maintain the balance, it's very hard to play for Black in a practical game as White owns the initiative. That's not a situation we aim for when playing the Spielmann-Indian, especially if there is a more energetic response available. Maybe you've already guessed it... }
9... Qb6
{ The queen manoeuvre is the hero once again. We hit the bishop and when it retreats Qxb2 wins a whole rook. That's too much a price, so White must keep his bishop on its current square. }
10. Na3
{ Very interesting. White defended the a3 knight by tactical means. The point is that after }
10... Bxb2 11. Nc4
{ The b5 bishop cannot be taken due to the fork on d6. White is threatening both the queen and the bishop, but we can counter with a threat of our own. }
11... Qg6
{ Not the first time we introduced this fine queen sortie! White has two moves now: the gambit  12.O-O!   or the structure-ruining  12.Ned6!?  We will examine the latter first. }
12. O-O
{ This knight sacrifice should be treated with care. After the natural  12...Bxa1  White will be able to generate ample compensation after  13.Nxc5  and it's not an easy job to defend against White's numerous threats. Moreover, I have avoided the greedy Bxa1 altogether in the 7. Bxb5 variation. Instead, I believe we should be brave and play with fire: take the knight! }
12... Qxe4
{ The exclamation mark isn't for the objective strength as  12...Bxa1  is probably better in an objective sense. However, don't mistake that this is an 'unsound move'. It also got the approval of the engine, just not as much as its rather greedy alternative. White's point is that with the forced }
13. Nd6+ exd6 14. Re1
{ He wins the queen, but that's not the end of the story. We will emerge with 2 minor pieces + 1 rook vs a queen, which is a very interesting material imbalance. In a normal situation, the three pieces should triumph over the queen, but here White has compensation due to our slightly exposed king. After a detailed analysis, I concluded that White's attack is probably only enough for dynamic equality or at most a symbolic edge. What we should aim for is to exchange all pieces and grind in the 3 pieces vs queen endgame in which we have better chances. }
14... Qe5 { This is the best way to give up the queen. } 15. Rxe5+ Bxe5 16. Rb1
{ White is threatening Bxd7, but actually it's not as good as it seems at first. }
16... Kd8 17. Qd3
{ The acid test of Black's queen sacrifice. White prevents Ba6 while hinting at a potential queen switch, for example, Qd3-b3 to increase the pressure. Initially, Stockfish gave White the status of 'clearly better', but at a great depth, the evaluation moved closer and closer to equal. We should immediately renew the threat of Ba6 with }
17... a5
{ The b7-bishop is so passive that we can afford a tempo to exchange it } 18.
Ba4
{ White should keep pieces on the board! In this position, we have to find an only move to defend against White's nasty threats. }
18... Bc8
{ For a concrete reason revealed later, the bishop should retreat to c8.  18...Ba6?  loses to  19.Qb3!  and the threat of Qb6+ is devastating. }
19. Qb3 Na6
{ This is the difference. The knight will interpose the check on c7 and White's attack come to an end after }
20. Qb6+ Nc7
{ While the engine displays the notorious 0.00, I prefer Black here. We have successfully stopped White's queenside initiative, and now it's our moment to strike on the other wing with all White's pieces on the queenside. Next on the agenda is h5-h4 to gain space on the kingside or Re8 followed by Bd4 in order to penetrate through the second rank.   Conclusion:   @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb1ppp1p/8/1ppP1p2/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bxb5  is a venomous sideline that we shouldn't underestimate. Both sides should be aware of the numerous tactical resources available. There are some moves that must be remembered by heart, but there are also common themes that appear again and again, for example, the Qd8-b6-g6 queen switch, and Black's continuing refusal to capture the a1-rook. }
