{ Regaining the f5-pawn isn't such a priority, but to seize the initiative is. White has two ways to defend the b2-pawn:  8.c3  is the strongest and a real attempt at an advantage while  8.Nc3  is meek and easy to deal with. There is also a dubious try, namely }
8. c3
{ Blunting the b7-bishop is actually a serious attempt at a refutation by my naive silicon engine. There is no satisfactory way to deviate since our 4th move 4...Bb7, so this position's evaluation represent the truth of the whole 4. Bg5 Bb7 variation. Initially, I was worried as even at a great depth the engine shows some advantage for White, but eventually, it calms down }
8... Qb6 { Simply protecting the b5-pawn } 9. a4
{ Undermining the b5-pawn for the c4 outpost, but we aren't going to give him that juicy square. }
9... a6 10. Na3
{ More and more forces are directed towards the foot soldier that stepped forward on the 3rd move. It has done its job, and now we should sacrifice it for something else! }
10... Qd6
{ This weird-looking manoeuvre is actually very effective. The d5-pawn is gone, even though at a cost... }
11. axb5 Qxd5 12. Qxd5 Bxd5
{ White shouldn't capture one more pawn because it's poisoned. } 13. bxa6
{ White took the pawn greedily, but we have healthy compensation after } 13...
Nxa6 14. Nc4 Nc7
{ Our bishop pair is powerful enough to secure us a balanced middlegame. } *

