[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Cori,J  vs. Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (3.c3, Iberoamericano 2020)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ First, we will take a look at a model game in the 3. c3 variation, played between two GMs, Jorge Cori and Iturrizaga Bonelli. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6
{ 2...c5  3.c3  b6  4.Bf4  Bb7  5.Nbd2  g6  6.e3  Bg7  7.Be2  O-O  Is the move-order in the course. }
3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. h3 c5 6. c3 b6 7. Nbd2 Bb7
{ Phew! After a London move order, the two players transposed to the 3. c3 b6 variation of the Spielmann-Indian, covered in this chapter. }
8. Be2 d6 { Black's plan is to force through e5. } 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Bh2
{ The usual London prophylactic retreat, avoiding any tactic connected with e5. }
10... a6
{ The Venezuelan grandmaster tried a creative plan: to play Ra7 followed by Qa8 to take control of the e4-square.   10...Qc7  This is another plan which has the idea of preparing e5.  11.Re1  Ne4=  And with e5 coming, Black is fine in this complex battle. }
11. a4 Ra7 12. Re1 Qa8 { The first step of the plan was finished. } 13. Bf1 Bc6
14. Qc2 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ Black has taken control of the centre, and at this point, he started to play on the queenside. }
16. Qd1 Rb8
{ The coordination of Black's major pieces is a pleasant picture. Look at that heavyweight queen and rooks boxed in the corner! }
17. Nd2 Bc6
{ Black's plan was crystal clear: to play on the queenside. Meanwhile, White really lacks an active plan. }
18. Bg3
{ This quiet bishop move did nothing to harm Black.   18.Nc4!?  This move might look counterintuitive as Black's plan is to push b5 anyway.  18...b5  19.Na5  White's idea is revealed: to block the a-file.  19...Bd5∞  White's knight is sidelined, but it's blocking our queenside play. I'd assess this position as dynamically balanced. }
18... b5 { Rip open the queenside. } 19. axb5 axb5 20. Bh4 Kf8
{ The king was perfectly safe, being just a square away from its home. } 21.
Nb3 { A rather pointless knight move. } 21... Ra4
{ Itturizaga tried an ingenious plan: to triple on the a-file.   21...b4∓  Is even stronger, utilizing the most from Black's forces. White is clearly lost in the queenside battle. }
22. Bg3 Rb6 23. dxc5 dxc5 24. Nd2 Rba6
{ The battle of the a-file is won by Black. } 25. Rxa4 Rxa4 26. Qb1 c4
{ Preparing a deadly knight invasion through c5. } 27. e4 Nc5 28. Bf4 Ra2 29.
f3 { White weakened the dark squares further. } 29... Ne6 30. Be3 Be5
{ Black is clearly winning due to White's terrible coordination. } 31. Rd1 Kg7
32. Be2 Bf4 33. Bf2
{ A blunder in time trouble.   33.Bxf4  Nxf4  34.Bf1  Qa7+  35.Kh1  Nh5-+  Is also winning for Black. }
33... Bxd2 34. Rxd2 Ra1 { The queen drops, and with it, the game. } 35. Rd1
Rxb1 36. Rxb1 Qa2
{ A remarkable performance in a blitz game by the Venezuelan GM. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Galliamova,A  vs. Pogonina,N (3.dxc5, Russian Championship 2020)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Next, we will examine a game played between two Russian players in the Women's section of the 2020 Russian Championship. It's a very instructive model game in the 3. dxc5 variation. Even though White never played Nf3 and transposed to that exact variation, the structure and pieces placement are strikingly similar. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 { 2.Nf3  c5  3.dxc5  Na6  Is covered in this chapter. } 2... c5
3. dxc5 Na6
{ Confronted with the harmless 3. dxc5, Pogonina tried a fun knight jump. } 4.
g3 Nxc5 5. Bg2
{ White had fianchettoed and applied some pressure on the long diagonal. Our plan is the same as in the main course: going for the double-fianchetto. }
5... g6 { Preparing Bg7. } 6. b4
{ Quiet development wouldn't trouble Black so White went for something more direct.   6.Nf3  Indeed, Black is in fine shape after simple development by White.  6...Bg7  7.O-O  b6=  Next, the second player will play Bb7 with a satisfactory middlegame. }
6... Ne6
{ The knight is very safe on e6. Yes, it blocks the e-pawn, but the bishops will be fianchettoed anyway.   6...Nce4  Is the crazy option, leads to an irrational position after the critical  7.f3!?  Bg7  8.fxe4   8.Bb2!?  The knight must spent further time  8...Ng5  9.f4  Ne6∞  With an incredibly complex position.  Ng8!  After this unintuitive knight retreat White loses the rook, but that's not the end of the story.  9.Bd2  Bxa1  10.Nc3  Bxc3  11.Bxc3=∞  White has rich compensation for the exchange; however, it's in doubt if it's enough. }
7. Bb2 Bg7 8. Nh3
{ The battle of creativity continues! White argues that the knight is well placed on h3 as it doesn't block the g2-bishop. }
8... a5
{ Black has so many viable alternatives here, but opening the a-file seems to be logical.   8...h5!?  Is another idea. Not the first time in this course Harry marches forward, right? }
9. a3 axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1 11. Bxa1 Qc7
{ Intending b7-b6 followed by Bb7/Ba6 to develop Black's last minor piece. }
12. Qd3 b6 13. O-O Ba6
{ Very ambitious. Black fought for more than equality.   13...Bb7  Exchanging White's fianchetto bishop isn't such a good idea as White's bishop is actually pointing at thin air. White can count on a slight advantage with  14.Bxb7  Qxb7  15.Nc3⩲  White's space advantage is enough for a slight edge. }
14. Nd2 O-O 15. e4 d6
{ Even though everything was still equal, Black is already more comfortable. The c4-pawn is particularly a vital weakness. }
16. f4
{ White couldn't accept the fact that she was on the defensive side and overextended.   16.Bb2  White should have wait patiently like this.  16...Rc8⩱  Black has a small advantage, but White isn't facing any serious threat either. }
16... b5
{ The opportunity presented itself and Pogonina didn't miss it. The main themes are the awkward placement of White's queen and rook and Black's ability to play Qb6+ with check @@StartBracket@@ this wasn't available before f2-f4@@EndBracket@@. }
17. c5
{ This is nothing but another way to lose material.   17.cxb5  Loses a bunch of material.  17...Qb6+  18.Rf2  Bxb5  Objectively the best way to win, but not the clearest.   18...Ng4  Also wins but in a more simple fashion.  19.Qf3  Nd4!  20.Bxd4  Qxd4-+  It's surprising that Black's advantage is around -6 here according to the engines, but White's busted anyway. The b4-pawn is doomed and all pieces are hyper-passive. }
17... dxc5 18. Bxf6
{ 18.bxc5?  Doesn't work due to  18...Qxc5+  19.Nf2  Rd8!  Bringing one more attacking unit into the battle. White cannot avoid huge material losses, as shown by  20.Qe2   20.Qc3  b4-+  White can resign.  Qc2  The d2-knight cannot escape now.  21.Rd1  Ng4-+  The final move of the combination. After everything is exchanged, the b-pawn will march to victory. }
18... Bxf6 19. e5 Bg7 20. Ra1 Rd8 21. Qe3 Bc8
{ Black is a clear pawn up with the unstoppable bishop pair. } 22. Nf2 f6
{ Activating the only passive Black piece. } 23. exf6 Bxf6 24. Rc1 c4
{ Nimzowitsch's dangerous criminal cannot be stopped. } 25. Nf3 Nd4 26. Ne5
Bxe5 27. fxe5 Bb7 28. h4 Bxg2 29. Kxg2
{ After some more simplifications Black was completely winning, and she nicely finished the game with an assault on White's king. }
29... Nf5 30. Qe2 Qc6+ 31. Kh3 Nd4 32. Qg4 Nf3 33. Rc3 Nxe5
{ One more pawn fell and the rest is easy. } 34. Qg5 Qe6+ 35. Kg2 Nd3 36. Ng4
Qe4+ 37. Kh2 Rd5 38. Nh6+ Kg7 39. Qd2 Rh5 40. Qd1 Kxh6
{ What a performance from Pogonina! This game perfectly illustrates Black's strategies to play for more than a draw in the 3. dxc5 variation. It's time to move on to the next one in the masterpieces collection. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Nguyen, Vuong Tung Lam vs. Le, Minh Hoang ( 3.g3, Vietnamese Championship 2020)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This game is a game between two of my compatriots. The white player is one of my closest friends @@StartBracket@@or rivals?@@EndBracket@@ who must be smiling when reading this. I don't want to make his defeat a model game at all, but it's a very instructive game for everyone to learn from. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ My friend is a fan of the 'Flashy Fianchetto' approach, even though it has brought him many disastrous defeats @@StartBracket@@ not just this one!@@EndBracket@@ }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3 d5 6. Bg2 Nc6
{ Seizing more space in the centre. Black is already slightly better now, by move 6@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@   6...a5!?  Is the direction I proposed in the course, but there is nothing wrong with the text move. }
7. Bg5
{ White embarked on a positional plan against d5, but it wouldn't work as Black's centre is too secure. }
7... Be6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3
{ White's pressure has reached its maximum, and his pieces started to be pushed back with }
9... d4 { 9...e4!?  Blunting the g2-bishop is also interesting. } 10. Bxf6
{ Practically forced to gain e4 for the knight.   10.Ne4?!  would have given Black the dream centre.  10...Nxe4  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Bxe4  O-O  ∓  Black has an impressive centre. Next, he should continue with Rd8 and f5 with an advantage. }
10... gxf6
{ Recapturing with the g-pawn is clearly superior as Black has the resource of f5 now. }
11. Ne4 Qb6
{ White's pieces were very passive and he had no active plan at all. But his next move is a deadly self-destructing one. }
12. f3
{ No comment can express my feeling when seeing this horrible move. White closed the diagonal of his own bishop and opened the b6-g1 diagonal at the same time. Probably White's idea is to prevent f5 followed by f4, but that's not as in Black's plan as h5-h4.   12.c3  Is a more active try, even though Black is still better after  12...f5  13.Ned2  dxc3  14.bxc3  h5!  With the participation of Harry, the attack will go strong. }
12... f5 13. Nf2 h5
{ There is a hook on g3, so Black immediately exploited it. His advantage is already decisive as White had NO counterplay. Black had all the time in the world to prepare a kingside attack, and the FM didn't miss the chance to bring home the point masterfully. }
14. Kh1 O-O-O 15. Qc1 Rdg8 16. c4 { Too late. } 16... h4
{ Look at White's pieces! } 17. g4 { A desperate attempt to close the g-file. }
17... h3 { The most elegant way to finish the game. } 18. Bxh3 Bg5
{ The bishop entered the fray. } 19. Qd1
{ 19.gxf5  Is the second choice of the engine, which is a testament to how lost White was at this point. }
19... fxg4 20. Bxg4 f5 { One more f-pawn! } 21. Bh3 Be3 22. Bg2 Qd8
{ From afar, Her Majesty swung to the queenside and White collapsed. } 23. Nh3
f4 24. Nf2 Qh4 25. h3 Rxg2
{ A beautiful demolition of White's kingside which forced resignation. Note that White's bishop is just a big pawn throughout the game, especially after the horrendous 12. f3??. After that, the attack played itself. Had White played on, the game's end would have been   26.Kxg2  Bxh3+  27.Nxh3  Qxh3# }
