[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Ftacnik, L  vs. Salem, A ( 3. c4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nc2, Olympiad Baku 2016)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ This is a model game in the 3. c4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nc2 variation. White was the great Lubomir Ftacnik and Black was GM Salem Saleh. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nc2
{ As I mentioned in the 3. c4 chapter, this is a harmless attempt at an advantage. Probably, GM Ftacnik wanted a quick draw?   5.Nb5!  The critical move, immediately targeting Black's weakness. }
5... d5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Qxd5 Nxd5 8. e4 Nb4 9. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11.
Nxd2
{ 11.Kxd2  Is the move given in my course, but both recaptures have equivalent value anyway. Check this line for more details about how to handle this symmetrical position. }
11... Ke7
{ The king was fully safe in the queenless middlegame, and it would be powerful in the endgame. }
12. Bc4 Nc6 { Eyeing the d4-square. } 13. Rc1 Rd8 14. Nf3
{ An awful positional blunder, overlooking Black's next move.   14.Ke2  Connecting the rooks is a better idea.  14...Nd4+  15.Ke3=  Both kings were perfectly placed in the centre, and the game should be drawn. }
14... Bg4
{ Salem threatened the f3-knight in order to remove the only defender of the d4-square. }
15. Bd5 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Nd4
{ Black was strategically close to winning as he had a golden knight on d4 which's far more superior than the d5-bishop. Furthermore, White's structure was really poor. }
17. Kd2
{ Ftacnik gave a worthless pawn in order to free his position.   17.Rc7+  This seemingly natural move actually trades White's most active piece.  17...Rd7  18.Rxd7+  Kxd7  19.Bxb7   19.Bxf7  Rc8∓  Is terrible for White with Rc2 coming.  Rb8-+  And Black is winning as White's queenside will be ripped apart. }
17... Ne6
{ Black declined the offer, but not in the most appropriate way.   17...Rac8!  Seizing the c-file.  18.Rc3  Rxc3  19.bxc3  Nxf3+∓  And Black is clearly better. }
18. Ke3 Rd7 19. Bxe6 Kxe6
{ Salem allowed his opponent to trade the minor pieces; however, White still faced a long and boring defensive task ahead. The isolated h-pawn was a big worry in particular. }
20. Rhd1 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Rc8
{ After just 21 moves the game fizzled out to a rook ending, and one in which Black alone had winning chances. We can conclude that it's a successful outcome out of the opening. The rest is a masterful endgame lesson by Black. }
22. Rd3 Rc2 23. Rb3 b6 24. Ra3 Rxb2 25. Rxa7 Kf6 26. a4 Ra2 27. Rb7 Rxa4 28.
Rxb6+ Kg5
{ After some accurate defending Ftacnik managed to eliminate the whole queenside, which greatly increased his drawing chances. Even though the engine displays the notorious 0.00, we humans understand that White's job of securing half a point is not done yet. }
29. Rb7 Kg6 30. Rb1 f6 31. Ke2 Ra3 32. Rg1+ Kh6 33. Rg4 g5 34. Rg1 Ra2+ 35. Ke3
{ 35.Kf1=  Would have been better, as the king will be useful on g2. } 35...
Kh5 36. Rb1 Ra7 37. Rb6 { White correctly activated his rook. } 37... Rf7 38.
f4
{ But he has gone over the extreme of activity! It's difficult to explain White such a world-class player like Ftacnik can make this blunder, voluntarily giving up a whole pawn.   38.Ke2!  Kh4  39.Kf1  Kh3  40.Kg1  Rd7  41.Kf1=  Is the only way to secure the draw. }
38... gxf4+ 39. Kf3 Kh4 40. Kg2 Rg7+ 41. Kf1 Rg6 42. f3 Kh3 43. Rb2 h5 44. Ra2
h4 45. Rb2 Rg8
{ Faced with the unstoppable threat of Ra8-a1+, forcing the king to leave the first rank and win the crucial h2-pawn, Ftacknik resigned. A well-earned win by GM Salem Saleh, after a tedious endgame grind. }
