[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Piceu,T - Zaragatski,I (3. d5 b5 4. c4 Bb7 5. a4, Belgium Team Championship 2019)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Now, we will take a look at a model game in the 3. d5 b5 4. c4 Bb7 5. a4 variation, which is covered in detail here }
1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. a4 Qa5+
{ The fine point. Black exploits the fact that the a5-e1 diagonal is open to force White's bishop to a clumsy square. }
6. Bd2 b4 7. Qc2 d6 8. e4 Nbd7
{ In the course I recommended   8...e5  ,  which is analyzed in a set of trainables. The text move leads to similar positions. }
9. Bd3 g6 { The bishop stands best on g7 in this type of structure. } 10. O-O
Bg7 11. h3 { Preventing a future Ng4-e5 manoeuver. } 11... O-O 12. Bf4
{ Supporting e4-e5. } 12... Qc7
{ The queen has no more duties on the queenside, so it comes back and holds up e4-e5. }
13. Nbd2 Rae8 14. Rfe1 Nh5 15. Bh2
{ Over the last few moves both sides have built up their forces, and it's Black to initiate action in the centre with the standard pawn break. }
15... e5 16. dxe6
{ Capturing en passant is practically forced.   16.Kh1  Or just about any sensible, waiting move would have given Black a risk-free kingside offensive after some preparatory manoeuvres. After the prophylactic  16...a5→  White's queenside counterplay is a dream and he has no counterplay at all. His pieces aren't well arranged to meet our f5 break either. }
16... fxe6
{ Allows White to complicate life.   16...Rxe6∓  would have been better. Re8 is coming next and Black's armies are coordinating wonderfully. }
17. e5
{ White seizes the moment to free the e4-square for his pieces and weakens Black's structure. In fact, any other move would give Black a crushing positional advantage after Nf4, but now White is back in the game. }
17... Nf4
{ Allows White to get the desired structure without sacrificing any material.   17...Nxe5  Bravely accepting the pawn. After  18.Nxe5  Bxe5  19.Bxe5  dxe5=  Our structure is broken, but our piece activity can compensate for this. Moreover, it's not easy for White to regain the pawn without making concessions. }
18. exd6 Qxd6 19. Be4
{ Exchanging White's inactive bishop for Black's powerful counterpart. } 19...
Bxe4 20. Nxe4
{ After some mistakes by Black, White emerged with a nice positional advantage. However, Black's actively-placed pieces meant that the second player could unleash some mighty tactical tricks, most notably Nxh3+. }
20... Qc6 21. Rad1 Nxh3+
{ An explosive and psychologically powerful sacrifice. With precise defending play, White can refute our sacrifice, but it's not gonna be a walk in the park. Alternatives like  21...Ne5  might be objectively better, but White's play is simple and straightforward in that event. To conclude, Black's sac was bluff, but he was immediately rewarded for his coward-style play. }
22. gxh3
{ Very natural, but actually a mistake.   22.Kf1!  Is the inhuman move that the engines found in seconds. Black is in trouble after  22...Nf6   22...Rxf3!?  23.gxf3  Ne5  Is another sacrifice to keep the momentum. However, Black is objectively lost here.  23.Rd6  Qa8  24.Be5!  White is dominating and nearly winning. }
22... Rxf3
{ Black was a pawn up and White's king was also insecure. However, White found the only way to save himself. }
23. Rd6 { Activity is the key! } 23... Qc8 24. Qd1
{ An effective double-attack. } 24... Rf7 { Forced. } 25. Ng5
{ Attacking the e6-pawn.   25.Rd2!?  However, this backward retreat is worth considering too. The idea is Nd6, so Black must react with  25...Ne5!  Meeting fire with fire. After the forced sequence  26.Nd6  Nf3+  27.Qxf3  Rxf3  28.Nxc8  Rxc8  We arrived at a balanced endgame which is most probably drawn with best play. }
25... Rf5 { Attacking f5 and set a nasty trap. } 26. Nxe6
{ And White fell for it! After building up an advantage, White let it slipped away, and now he blundered }
26... Ne5 { Is the point, threatening Nf3. } 27. Kf1 Nf3
{ The knight joined the battle with decisive effect. } 28. Rd7
{ Now, Black finished things off with } 28... Nxh2+ 29. Kg2 Qc6+
{ With either mate or big material losses coming, White threw in the towel. } *

