[Black "Tkachiev,V  vs. Ivanchuk,V (3. d5 b5 4. c4 Bb7 5. Qc2, European Championship 2010)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Now, we will see a model game in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2ppppp/5n2/1ppP4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Bb7  5.Qc2!?  variation. White was GM Tkachiev, while the player handling Black's cause is the legendary Ivanchuk. Even though the position started with a different move order, it will transpose anyway. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. Qc2
{ White intended e2-e4 to support the d5-pawn. I covered this variation in-depth here. }
5... bxc4 6. e4 e6 7. Bxc4
{ 7.dxe6  fxe6!?  is analysed in the course, as well as   7.Bg5  exd5!? } 7...
exd5 8. exd5 Bxd5 9. Bxd5 Nxd5 10. O-O Be7 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Qxc5 Nf6
{ So far both players had played the opening phase perfectly. } 13. Qf5
{ 13. Nc3 is given in the course, but Tkachiev's novelty is also playable. }
13... O-O 14. Nc3 d5
{ Ivanchuk preferred to advance immediately in the centre, but the decision was premature. The structural imbalance is very interesting: White has fewer pawn islands, but on the other hand, the d5-pawn is controlling many squares in the centre. White's queenside might be a target for our heavy pieces, too. However, White had a resource that made Ivanchuk's decision questionable.   14...Qb6  Would have transposed to my recommendation. }
15. Bg5 { Putting pressure on Ivanchuk's center. } 15... h6 16. Bh4
{ 16.Bxf6!  was more precise.  16...Bxf6  17.Nxd5  Bxb2  18.Rad1±  White's pieces are centralized and he has a big initiative. }
16... Rb8
{ The d5-pawn would fall at some point, so Ivanchuk started counterplay against White's queenside. }
17. Rad1 d4
{ The only way to maintain the pawn, but it gave White the advantage.   17...Rxb2!?  Leads to a roughly equal ending after  18.Bxf6  Bxf6  19.Nxd5  Qd6  20.Nxf6+  Qxf6  21.Qxf6  gxf6=  White is pressing, but Black should hold the draw. Understandably, Ivanchuk wanted more. }
18. Nb5 g6
{ The b5-knight was vulnerable, so Black kicked White's queen around. } 19. Qd3
Nb4 20. Qc4 d3
{ Tkachiev should have bravely taken the free pawn with  21.Nxa7 } 21. a3
{ Seemingly Black's position was hopeless, but there was a brilliant resource on offer, which Ivanchuk missed.   21.Nxa7  Rb7  22.a3!  When White is simply a pawn up. }
21... Nc2
{ 21...Qd5!  A powerful intermezzo.  22.Qxd5  Nbxd5  23.a4  Bb4=∞  Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn due to his pressure on the queenside. }
22. Rf1
{ No words can explain the reason White played this awful move.   22.Re5!  Would have brought Tkachiev a decisive advantage as d3 is bound to fall }
22... Qd5 { Ivanchuk didn't miss it again. } 23. Qxd5 Nxd5 24. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ It's clear that White can no longer protect the b2-pawn. } 25. Nc3
{ 25.Nd6  Is met by  25...Rfd8   25...Rxb2=  Is also fine  26.Rxd3  Nf5  Black still has ongoing pressure }
25... Rfd8
{ The far-advanced d3-pawn is far more important than the unmoved b2-pawn. White was already playing for a draw, and in the game, he failed to find the way. }
26. Ne5
{ 26.Na4!  Is the only way to hold, but Black is still in the driver's seat.  26...Nc6⩱  Nd4 is coming. }
26... Rxb2 27. Ne4 Nxa3
{ Black is a pawn up. The rest is a matter of technique. Even though it's not so easy to convert this into a win, I won't annotate the rest of the game because it's beyond what we need to know about the Spielmann-Indian. }
28. Rxd3 Rxd3 29. Nxd3 Rb6 30. Ra1 Rb1+ 31. Rxb1 Nxb1 32. Nd6 Na3 33. Ne5 f5
34. f4 Kg7 35. Kf2 Nc2 36. Ke2 Nd4+ 37. Kd3 Ndc6 38. Nd7 Nd5 39. g3 Nf6 40. Ke3
Nxd7
{ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Tkachiev,V  @@StartBracket@@2636@@EndBracket@@-Ivanchuk,V @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2010 }
