[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Mantovani,R vs. Davies,N ( 3. d5 b5 4. a4, Saint Vincent 1999)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is a model game in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d5  b5  4.a4  variation. The player who handled Black was GM Nigel Davies, a renowned chess player and educator. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4 b4 5. c4 e6 6. dxe6
{ 6.Bg5  Is the critical continuation, analysed in the course here. } 6... fxe6
{ Davies preferred imbalances; after all, he was the rating favourite.   6...dxe6=  The resulting position after the other recapture is quite drawish due to the symmetrical structure. }
7. g3 Bb7 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4 Nc6 11. Nbd2
{ White deviated from the course. However, the plans and structure are very similar. Also, Black has the useful resource of Nh5, hunting down the aggressively-placed f4-bishop.   11.Bd6  I 'only' mentioned this move in the course. I continue the line some moves further here.  11...Na5  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Nbd2  d5∓  And Black is clearly better. }
11... Na5
{ From a5 the knight has the function of tying White's knight to the uncomfortable d2-square. }
12. Qc2 Nh5
{ Black's creative knight jumps left him with two knights on the rim, however, they weren't dim at all!   12...Qb6!?  Is another idea, preparing d5.  13.Rad1  d5∞  The position is still very complicated. }
13. Be3
{ Of course White cannot keep the bishop on f4.   13.Be5?  Is, of course, a blunder due to  13...d6-+  And the mighty bishop found itself hopelessly trapped in the middle of the board. }
13... Rc8 14. Rad1 Nf6 { The knight has done its job, it's time to return. }
15. h4
{ White's idea is to create an outpost on g5 for his minor pieces. However, this plan is quite committal as the g4-square is forever weakened.   15.b3  Is a more flexible and solid alternative, strengthening White's queenside. }
15... Qe8
{ A very typical queen switch in this kind of position. The queen heads for either h5 or g6, if possible. }
16. Bg5 Kh8 17. Bxf6
{ A questionable decision. White voluntarily gave up the bishop pair without anything to compensate for it. }
17... gxf6
{ Recapturing with the g-pawn is best as the pawn controls the g5-square, thus avoiding Ng5 tricks. Black is clearly better with the bishop pair, a flawless position and the semi-open g-file.   17...Bxf6  Would be a mistake.  18.Ng5!  Is the small tactic White counted on when playing 17. Bxf6  18...Bxg5  19.Bxb7  Nxb7  20.hxg5±  White is clearly better due to his superior piece activity. }
18. Nb3
{ White offered a trade to minimize the disadvantage of his space disadvantage. }
18... Nc6
{ Declining the trade.   18...Nxb3!  Is better, with a concrete idea.  19.Qxb3  d5∓  Black is in time to execute this break, with a harmonious position. }
19. Qd2 Nb8
{ Yes, the d7-pawn was threatened, but passive defence like this wasn't needed at all.   19...d6  A much simpler way to defend the pawn. }
20. Qe3 Bc6 21. Ra1
{ White unnecessarily put one of his rooks back on the original square just to defend the measly a4-pawn.   21.Na5!  Gambitting the pawn for some positional compensation.  21...Bxa4  22.Ra1  Bc6  23.Nxc6  Nxc6∞  White is still a pawn down but the a-pawn can be blocked at any time, while the g2-bishop is a potential monster. }
21... Rg8 22. Nbd2 Qg6 { Davies slowly brought his armies to the attack. } 23.
Ne1 f5 24. Ndf3 Qg7
{ Taking aim at the b2-pawn.   24...d6  Preparing e5 is objectively stronger, but Davies's move is also strong. }
25. Nd3 Bf6 26. Rab1
{ 26.Nxc5?  Would lost a piece.  26...Bxf3!  Removing the defender of the d4-square.  27.Bxf3  Bd4-+  And the knight is lost. }
26... Be4 27. b3 Nc6 28. Rbd1 Nd4 { Black's forces were in full speed. } 29.
Nf4 Bxf3
{ The f3-knight was the best defensive piece, so Davies removed it from the battle. }
30. exf3
{ 30.Bxf3  Isn't better either.  30...e5-+  White is dead lost with numerous threats like f4,e4 and Bxh4. }
30... Qh6 { Preparing the final breakthrough. } 31. Rd3 e5 32. Nd5 f4
{ Crashing through White's defences. } 33. Qd2 Bxh4 34. Rd1
{ 34.gxh4  There's already a forced mate.  34...Rxg2+!  35.Kxg2  Rg8+  36.Kh3  Nf5-+  Mate is unavoidable. }
34... Qg7 { The sad g-pawn must advance in order to avoid immediate death. }
35. g4 h5 { The g4-pawn was helplessly pinned to the bishop. } 36. Bh3 Rc6
{ Davies sent his rook to the kingside, but there was a neater finish.   36...Nxf3+!!  Is a killer.  37.Rxf3  hxg4-+  White's pieces would fall like ripe fruit, like the fact that the engine showed  38.Rg3  as the best move suggests. }
37. Kh1 Rg6 38. Rg1 d6 39. Rg2 Qh7 40. Rh2 Rh6 41. Qd1 hxg4 42. Bxg4 Bg3
{ A spectacular end to a fascinating game by GM Nigel Davies. It's mate after 43. Rxh6 Qxh6+ followed by Qh2+. }
