[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "Sanchez Guirado,F vs. Garcia Roman, D ( 3. d5 b5 4. Bg5, Valencia 2009)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is a model game in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d5  b5  4.Bg5  variation, the most critical line of the whole course. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Bg5 Bb7 5. c4
{ Objectively this is worse than  5.Bxf6  ,  but there was no theory about this line back in 2006, and even now.   5.Bxf6  Is the mainline, analysed in this chapter.  5...gxf6  6.e4  f5!?  Leads to double-edged play. }
5... Ne4 6. Bf4 bxc4 7. Nc3 Qa5 8. Bd2 Nxd2 9. Nxd2 Ba6 10. e4 g6 11. Bxc4 Bg7
12. O-O O-O 13. Qe2 d6
{ This is where the line ends in this course. Coincidentally, both players had followed my course for 13 moves, which is actually an impressive number considering that most of the lines in the course are original. I boasted so many times about the originality of the course, but this time I must confess that someone came before me. Black has excellent play on the b-file, and the Dragon bishop is unopposed on the long diagonal. }
14. Rfc1 Bxc4 15. Nxc4 Qa6
{ The queen is perfectly placed here, supporting the queenside play. White's pieces look good, but in reality, he has no active plan at all. Black is already slightly better. }
16. a4
{ White wants to somehow block the b-file with Nb5, but this create an unnecessary weakness.   16.b3  Passive defence is required.  16...Nd7  17.Rc2  Nb6⩱  Black is still somewhat better, but there isn't the weakness on b3 as in the game. }
16... Nd7 17. Nb5 Rab8
{ Simple and strong. White must sit and watch Garcia improve his position. }
18. Ra3 Nb6 { Exchanging the best defender, the c4-knight. } 19. Qd2 Nxc4 20.
Rxc4 Qb6
{ Preparing a6 when White's queenside fall apart. Note the difference between the strength of the minor pieces. }
21. Rb3 a6 22. Nd4
{ The only move, threatening Black's queen while defending the rook. Garcia correctly declined the tempting queen sacrifice. }
22... Qc7
{ There is no need to be flashy.   22...Qxb3  23.Nxb3  Rxb3∓  Is better for Black as well, but the material imbalance means that White can still generate some counterplay. }
23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. Nc6 Rxb2
{ Finally, this pawn dropped, and with it, the game. } 25. Rc2 Rb1+ 26. Rc1 Rb3
27. Qa2 Rb2 28. Qc4 Qb7 29. h3 Bf6 30. Re1 Rd2 31. Re2 Qb1+ 32. Kh2 Qf1
{ And the devastating pin caused White to resign. A fantastic performance by Garcia, who dominated his opponent from start to finish with the Spielmann-Indian. }
